# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: american-revolutionary-war
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] The New World of the Western Hemisphere was devastated by the **1775–1782 North American smallpox epidemic**.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] Estimates based on remnant settlements say at least 130,000 people were estimated to have died from smallpox in the epidemic that started in 1775.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] Controversially at the time, George Washington, the Commander-in-Chief of the Continental Army, required troops in the Continental Army be inoculated against smallpox in 1777.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] Smallpox was long known as a dangerous disease, and though it is today known to be caused by a virus, this was not known in the eighteenth century.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] The most common type of smallpox, ordinary, historically has devastated populations with a 30% death rate.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] The smallpox virus is transmittable through bodily fluids and materials contaminated with infected materials.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] Generally, face-to-face contact is required for an individual to contract smallpox as a result of an interaction with another human.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] Unlike some viruses, humans are the only carriers of variola major.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] This limits the chances of the virus being unknowingly spread through contact with insect or other animal populations.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] Persons infected with smallpox are infectious to others for about 24 days after their infection time.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] However, there is a period of time in which individuals are contagious but have only begun to experience minor symptoms such as fever, headaches, body aches, nausea, pustules, pox, and sometimes vomiting.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] Prevention of its spread through inoculation had been practiced in China, Turkey, and parts of Africa.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] A smallpox epidemic in Boston in 1721 divided Bostonians.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] Famed Puritan minister, Cotton Mather learning about inoculation from his enslaved black servant, advocated for its use.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] Opposed to it was the leading physician of the era.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] This epidemic occurred during the years of the American Revolutionary War.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] During this time, there was no medical technology widely available to protect soldiers from outbreaks in crowded and unhygienic troop camps.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] Thus, this virus posed a major threat to the success of the Continental Army, led by George Washington.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] It is not known where the outbreak began, but the epidemic was not limited to the colonies on the Eastern seaboard, nor to the areas ravaged by hostilities.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] The outbreak spread throughout the North American continent.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] In 1775, it was already raging through British-occupied Boston and among the Continental Army's invasion of Canada.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] During George Washington's siege of Boston, the disease broke out among both Continental and British camps.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] Many escaped slaves who had fled to the British lines in the South likewise contracted smallpox and died.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] The pandemic had also reached New Spain, spreading through Texas and New Orleans through 1778 to 1779.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] The latter was especially hard hit due to its densely populated urban area.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] By 1779, the disease had spread to Mexico and would cause the deaths of tens of thousands.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] At its end, the epidemic had crossed the Great Plains, reaching as far west as the Pacific coast, as far north as Alaska, and as far south as Mexico, infecting virtually every part of the continent.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] The pandemic also took a massive toll on the indigenous population of the Americas.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] The disease was likely spread via the travels of the Shoshone Indian tribes.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] Beginning in 1780, it reached the Pueblos of the territory comprising present day New Mexico.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] It also showed up in the interior trading posts of the Hudson's Bay Company in 1782.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] It affected nearly every tribe on the continent, including the northwestern coast.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] It is estimated to have killed nearly 11,000 Native Americans in the Western area of present-day Washington, reducing the population from 37,000 to 26,000 in just seven years.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] Though there was not too much known about viruses and their transitions, English colonists in North America recognized the effectiveness of isolating individuals infected with smallpox.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] The English colonies were more aware of the features of smallpox than of almost any other infectious disease.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] It was widely recognized that there were only two options for protecting oneself against this disease, quarantine or inoculation against the disease.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] Many feared inoculation, and instead chose isolation via quarantine.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] Individuals with recognized infections were sent to remote locations where they could let the disease run its course without the fear of infecting others.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] If needed, the scale of the quarantine could be increased.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] This meant cutting off entire towns from the rest of the colonies for the duration of the disease.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] Members of the English colonies as well as English officials were proactive in establishing quarantine guidelines in order to protect the public.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] One of the earliest recorded examples of this was a quarantine established in 1647 by Puritans in order to prevent the spread of disease from ships coming from the Caribbean.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] In 1731, an act, entitled "An Act to Prevent Persons From Concealing the Smallpox", was passed.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] This act made the heads of households mandatory reporters for smallpox; these individuals were required to report smallpox in their house to the selectmen of the Massachusetts Bay Colony.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] Infected households would then be indicated with the placement of a red flag.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] In South Carolina, sentinels were to be posted outside infected households and infectious notices were required to be posted.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] In many colonies islands were set up to quarantine individuals coming in by ship.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] This decreased the chances of smallpox being introduced via trade or travel.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] By the late 18th century, almost all colonies had quarantine laws in effect in order to diminish the hugely damaging effects that smallpox could have on their communities.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] Upon taking charge of the Continental Army, Washington recognized the severe danger that smallpox posed to his men and the outcome of the war.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] To this end, Washington became "particularly attentive to the least Symptoms of Smallpox" among his men.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] Further, Washington was prepared to quarantine any member of his troops showing symptoms according to previously discovered methods and guidelines, including through the use of a special hospital.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] Following an outbreak of smallpox in Boston, Washington took further precautions to protect his men; he quarantined his men from the dangerous Boston public.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] These measures included the refusal to allow contact between his soldiers and the viral refugees of Boston.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] Additionally, certain retreats of the Continental Army can be linked to Washington's wish to avoid smallpox and his intense caution when it came to his troops.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] Though it was practiced in many parts of the world, the technology of inoculation, or variolation, was not in use in Europe apart from Wales, where it was reportedly in use as early as 1600.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] The practice was widely publicized over a century later by Lady Mary Wortley Montagu, who inoculated her own children against smallpox, despite widespread concern and controversy.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] Inoculation was the practice of introducing infected materials into the bodies of healthy individuals with the hope that they would contract a mild form of smallpox, recover, and be immune to further infections.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] The outcome of inoculations in surviving patients was successful.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] These individuals proved to be immune to smallpox.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] Understandably, there was much concern surrounding the practice of inoculation.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] The ordinary person was unable to comprehend the efficacy of intentionally infecting an otherwise healthy person with a potentially fatal disease.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] Thus, many were reluctant to have themselves or their family members inoculated.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] There were instances in which these fears were validated.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] Many of those who had been inoculated died as a result of the smallpox they had been exposed to.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] Additionally, there was the potential for an accidental outbreak of smallpox after contact between inoculation patients and the public.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] The choice of significant individuals such as John Adams and Abigail Adams to be inoculated did some to make inoculations more accepted, but there was still much progress to be made.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] George Washington contributed greatly to the progression of public health systems in America.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] During his time working with the Continental Army, Washington observed how smallpox and other diseases spread through Army camps and gatherings.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] This was often due to the cramped and dirty living conditions of these places.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] Washington understood the destructive nature of smallpox and other diseases such as malaria, diphtheria, and scarlet fever.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] He was one of the first to introduce the idea of compulsory health initiatives such as widespread inoculation.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] Washington also had experience with disease outside the realm of combat and war.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] Having himself suffered from many illnesses and observing those of his family, George Washington was an integral part of the establishment of American public health programs.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] Along with quarantine, another one of Washington's methods for keeping his men healthy was with the use of inoculation.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] Washington, like others of the time period, was not intimately familiar with the exact mechanisms of the virus.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] However, he and others were able to realize that men who had previously contracted and subsequently recovered from smallpox were unlikely to become ill a second time.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] Thus, early on Washington recognized the strategic advantage of these individuals.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] During an outbreak in Boston, Washington sent troops made up only of men who had previously been infected with smallpox.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] With this, he was able to both protect his soldiers and take advantage of the vulnerability of Boston and its British inhabitants during the smallpox outbreak of March 1776.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] Initially, George Washington was reluctant to inoculate his troops.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] But as he watched many of his men fall victim to smallpox, Washington believed that he would be able to keep his troops healthy through sanitary and quarantine methods.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] There were several events that contributed to the change of Washington's policy.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] First, Washington recognized that quarantine and attempted cleanliness were not enough to keep his vital troops healthy and in fighting form.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] Additionally, many prominent members of colonial society were having themselves and their families inoculated.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] Eventually, even George Washington's wife, Martha Washington was herself inoculated.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] It was not long after this that Washington initiated the inoculation of the American troops.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] Washington recognized the dangers of inoculating these men; many patients died as result of the infection caused by inoculation.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] However, the importance of keeping his men healthy outweighed the risks, and almost all Continental soldiers were inoculated against smallpox.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] Local officials were concerned that the inoculation of soldiers would lead to the accidental spread of smallpox among civilians.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] But Washington persisted in his quest and managed to get the majority of his soldiers inoculated.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] Along with the rise in popularity of the practice, Washington's decision to inoculate his troops was also extremely strategic; he was able to realize the deep impact an epidemic would have on his troops.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] Immunity was initially more widespread among the British men than the Americans.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] This was due to the more accepted practice of inoculation in Europe and the high rate of childhood cases, resulting in immunity.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] With this, an epidemic spread among Americans could prove disastrous to the American cause.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] With his men at Valley Forge inoculated, Washington was able to proceed with more confidence, knowing that at least his men would not be struck down by the smallpox virus.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] Both John and Abigail Adams were intimately familiar with disease and illness, having seen many family members and themselves infected.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] Thus, Abigail made certain to educate her children on the dangers of disease and how to best avoid it.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] These lessons included both practices of cleaning and the administration of home medicine.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] The Adams both understood the toll that smallpox could take and therefore feared the disease and its potentially devastating lasting effects.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] In July 1764, John Adams set an example by choosing to be inoculated before it was a commonly accepted practice.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] Though techniques were rudimentary at this time, Adams survived the experience, emerging with protective immunity.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] Warren my brother's [probably Peter Boylston Adams].
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] and with their Points divided the skin about a Quarter of an inch and just suffering the blood to appear, buried a thread (infected) about a Quarter of an inch long in the Channell.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] With this act, John Adams set a precedent for many.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] At the time of his inoculation, the practice was still highly controversial and distrusted by most.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] This stemmed from the cases in which inoculation patients died as a result of the contracted disease.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] Additionally, there was always the risk of inoculation patients unintentionally infecting others.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] However, Adams understood that the benefits of inoculation far outweighed the potential risks.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] Having a background in medicine, Adams strove to educate others on his findings and beliefs.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] John Adams was certainly a leading figure in the American Revolution; he played many important roles and was known to many.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] Adams was able to spread his progressive beliefs about public health programs such as inoculation by taking advantage of his status during this time.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] In July 1776, Abigail and their four children, Charles, Nabby, Thomas, and John Quincy, were all inoculated.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] Many of the leading figures associated with the American Revolution were also involved in the attempt to stop the disastrous spread of smallpox throughout the American Colonies and beyond.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] Such individuals included George Washington, Thomas Jefferson, John Adams, and Benjamin Franklin, among others.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] Prior to the steps made by these parties, public health policies in the colonies were not well established; they were limited to emergency situations.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] This is to say that policies and programs sprung up around epidemics and quarantines, wherever they were needed in the moment.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] However, the scourge of smallpox prompted changes to be made that would impact the public health of America for years to come.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] At the time of its introduction, almost all colonists were extremely wary of this new medical procedure.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] It was difficult for them to understand how the infection of an otherwise healthy individual could have a positive outcome.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] However, inoculation saved many lives and may have protected the Continental Army from destruction.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1775-82-north-american-smallpox-epidemic] The smallpox inoculation program paved the way for the global public health system that is responsible for the control and eradication of many deadly diseases, including but not limited to polio, measles, and diphtheria.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1776-in-the-united-states] 1776 is celebrated in the United States as the official beginning of the nation, with the Declaration of Independence of the Thirteen Colonies from the British Empire issued on July 4.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] The **1811 German Coast uprising** was a slave rebellion which occurred in the Territory of Orleans on January 8–10, 1811.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] It occurred on the east bank of the Mississippi River in the modern-day Louisiana parishes of St.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] The rebellion was the largest of its kind in the history of the United States.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] The rebels killed two white slave owner family members, but the confrontations with the U.S. military and local militiamen who were sent to suppress the rebellion, combined with post-trial executions, resulted in the deaths of 95 rebels.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] On January 8, between 64 and 125 slaves ignited a fight for freedom and marched from plantations in and near present-day LaPlace, Louisiana on the German Coast towards New Orleans.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] More people escaped slavery and joined them along the way, and some accounts claimed a total of 200 to 500 people escaped and participated in the rebellion.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] During their two-day, 20 mi (32 km)-long march the rebels, armed mostly with improvised weapons, burned five plantations along with several sugarhouses and crop fields.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] After a few planters were killed and others attacked, White settlers led by U.S. officials formed militia companies.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] In battle on January 10 they killed 40 to 45 of the people escaping slavery, while suffering no fatalities themselves, then hunted down and killed several other people without trial.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Over the next two weeks, White planters and U.S. officials interrogated, tried, executed, and decapitated an additional 44 people escaping slavery who had been captured.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Executions were generally by hanging or firing squad.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Heads were displayed on pikes to intimidate others.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Since 1995, the African American History Alliance of Louisiana has led an annual commemoration in January of the uprising, in which they have been joined by some descendants of participants in the revolt.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] The sugar boom on what was known as Louisiana's German Coast (named for immigrants in the 1720s) began after the American Revolutionary War, while the area near New Orleans was still controlled by Spain.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] In the 1780s Jean Saint Malo, an escaped slave, established a colony of maroons in the swamps below New Orleans, which eventually led Spanish officials to send militia to capture him.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Saint Malo became a folk hero after his execution in New Orleans on June 19, 1784.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] A decade later, during the height of the French Revolution, Spanish officials discovered a slave conspiracy at Pointe Coupee (established by French settlers around 1720 between Natchez and New Orleans).
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] That slave uprising during the Easter holidays was suppressed before it came to fruition and resulted in 23 executions by hanging (with the severed heads then displayed on the road to New Orleans), and 31 additional slaves were flogged and sent to serve hard labor in other Spanish outposts.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] After the Haitian Revolution, planters established similar lucrative sugarcane plantations in the Gulf Coast area, resulting in a dense slave population.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] They converted from cotton and indigo plantations to sugarcane, so that by 1802, 70 sugar plantations produced over 3,000 tons annually.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Some accounts claimed blacks outnumbered whites by nearly five to one by 1810, and about 90% of whites in the area enslaved people.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] More than half of those enslaved may have been born outside Louisiana, many in Africa, where various European nations established slave trading outposts and Kongo was ripped apart by civil wars.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] After the U.S. negotiated the Louisiana Purchase in 1803, both the Marquis de Lafayette and James Monroe declined to become the governor of the Territory of Orleans.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] President Thomas Jefferson then turned to a fellow Virginian, William C.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Claiborne, whom he appointed on an interim basis and who arrived in New Orleans with 350 volunteers and 18 boats.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Claiborne struggled with the area's diverse population, particularly because he spoke neither French nor Spanish.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] The population also included a larger proportion of native Africans among the slaves than elsewhere in the U.S.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] In addition, the mixed-race Creole and French-speaking population grew markedly with refugees from Haiti (and their slaves) following the successful Haitian Revolution.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Claiborne was not used to a society with the number of free people of color that Louisiana had, but he worked to continue their role in the militia that had been established under Spanish rule.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Long-term French Creole residents complained to Washington, D.C., about Claiborne and new U.S. settlers in the territory, and wanted no part of President Jefferson's plan to pay 30,000 Americans to move into the new territory and amalgamate with the residents.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Thus, by 1805, a delegation led by Jean Noël Destréhan went to Washington to complain about the "oppressive and degrading" form of the territorial government, but President Madison continued to support Claiborne, who had expressed great doubts about the planters' honesty and trustworthiness.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Lastly, Claiborne suspected that the Spanish in nearby West Florida might encourage an insurrection.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Thus, he struggled to establish and maintain his authority.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] In the overall Territory of Orleans, from 1803 to 1811, the free black population nearly tripled, to 5,000, with 3,000 arriving as migrants from Haiti (via Cuba) in 1809–1810.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] In Saint-Domingue they had enjoyed certain rights as *gens de couleur*, including owning slaves themselves.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Furthermore, between 1790 and 1810, slave traders brought around 20,000 enslaved Africans to New Orleans.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] The masters and slaves were virtually all Catholic.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] The waterways and bayous around New Orleans and Lake Pontchartrain made transportation and trade possible but also provided easy escapes and nearly impenetrable hiding places for runaway slaves.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Some maroon colonies continued for years within several miles of New Orleans.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] With the spread of ideas of freedom from the French and Haitian Revolutions, European Americans worried about slave uprisings, particularly in the Louisiana area.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] In 1805, they heard a traveling Frenchman was preaching about liberty, equality, and fraternity to the French-speaking slaves, and arrested him as dangerous.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] A group of slaves met on January 6, 1811.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] It was a period when work had relaxed on the plantations after the fierce weeks of the sugar harvest and processing.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] As planter James Brown testified weeks later, "The black Quamana [Kwamena, meaning "born on Saturday"], owned by Mr.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Brown, and the mulatto Harry, owned by Messrs.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Kenner and Henderson, were at the home of Manuel Andry on the night of Saturday–Sunday of the current month in order to deliberate with the mulatto Charles Deslondes, chief of the brigands." Slaves had spread word of the planned uprising among the slaves at plantations up and down the German Coast.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] The revolt began on January 8 at the Andry plantation.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] After striking and badly wounding Andry, the slaves killed his son Gilbert.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] "An attempt was made to assassinate me by the stroke of an axe", Andry wrote.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] "My poor son has been ferociously murdered by a horde of brigands who from my plantation to that of Mr.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] The approximately 15 slaves at Andry's plantation, about 30 miles (50 km) upriver from New Orleans, joined another eight slaves from the next-door plantation of the widows of Jacques and Georges Deslondes.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] This was the home plantation of Charles Deslondes, a slave driver (a slave overseer of other slaves) later described by one of the captured slaves as the "principal chief of the brigands".
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Small groups of slaves joined from every plantation the rebels passed.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Witnesses remarked on their organized march.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] They carried mostly pikes, hoes, and axes, but few firearms, and they marched to drums while some carried flags.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Approximately 10–25% of any given plantation's slave population joined with them.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] At the plantation of James Brown, Kook, one of the most active participants and key figures in the story of the uprising, joined the insurrection.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] At the next plantation down, Kook attacked and killed François Trépagnier with an axe.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] He was the second and last planter killed in the rebellion.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] After the band of slaves passed the LaBranche plantation, they stopped at the home of the local physician.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Finding him gone, Kook set his house on fire.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Some planters testified at the trials in parish courts that they were warned by slaves of the uprising.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Others regularly stayed in New Orleans, where many had town houses, and trusted their plantations to overseers to run.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Planters quickly crossed the Mississippi River to escape the insurrection and to raise a militia.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] As those escaping moved downriver, they passed larger plantations, from which other slaves joined them.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Numerous slaves joined the insurrection from the Meuillion plantation, the largest and wealthiest plantation on the German Coast.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] The rebels laid waste to Meuillion's house.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] They tried to set it on fire, but a slave named Bazile fought the fire and saved the house.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] The uprising started in present-day LaPlace and followed a 20-mile trek on the old River Road through the present-day towns of Montz, Norco, New Sarpy, Destrehan, St.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Rose and ended at much of what had once been the Kenner and Henderson Plantations and is now Rivertown and Louis Armstrong International Airport in Kenner.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] After nightfall the escaping slaves reached Cannes-Brulées, about 15 miles (24 km) northwest of New Orleans.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] The men had traveled between 14 and 22 miles (23 and 35 km), a march that probably took them seven to ten hours.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] By some accounts, they numbered "some 200 slaves", although other accounts estimated up to 500.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] As typical of revolts of most classes, free or slave, the insurgent slaves were mostly young men between the ages of 20 and 30.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] They represented primarily lower-skilled occupations on the sugar plantations, where slaves labored in difficult conditions with a low life expectancy.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Despite his injuries, Andry crossed the river and made contact with other planters, raising a militia and pursuing the escaping slaves.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] By noon on January 9, the residents of New Orleans had heard about the insurrection.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] By sunset, General Wade Hampton I, Commodore John Shaw, and Claiborne sent two volunteer militia companies, 30 US Army soldiers, and 40 US Navy sailors to fight the escaping slaves.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] By about 4 a.m. on January 10, this force had reached Jacques Fortier's plantation, where Hampton thought the escaped slaves had encamped overnight.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] However, the escaped slaves had started back upriver about two hours earlier, had traveled about 15 miles (24 km) back up the coast, and had neared Bernard Bernoudy's plantation.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] There, planter Charles Perret, in cooperation with Andry and Judge St.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Martin, had assembled a militia of about 80 men from the river's opposite side.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] At about 9 o'clock, this militia force discovered escaping slaves moving toward high ground on Bernoudy's plantation.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Perret ordered his men to attack the escaping slaves, which he later wrote numbered about 200 men, about half on horseback.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] (Most accounts said only the leaders were mounted, and historians believe it unlikely the escaping men could have gathered so many mounts.) Within a half-hour, 40 to 45 escaping people had been killed; the remainder slipped away into the woods and swamps.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Perret's and Andry's militias tried to pursue them despite the difficult terrain.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] On January 11, the militia, assisted by Native American trackers as well as hunting dogs, captured Deslondes, whom Andry considered "the principal leader of the bandits." A slave driver and son of a white man and a slave, Deslondes received no trial or interrogation.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] The following day Pierre Griffee and Hans Wimprenn, who were thought the murderers of M.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] François Trépagnier, were captured, killed, and their heads decapitated for delivery to the Andry estate.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Major Milton and the dragoons from Baton Rouge arrived and provided support for the militia, since Hampton believed them supported by Spanish authorities in West Florida.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Having suppressed the insurrection, the planters and government officials continued to search for people who had escaped.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Those captured later were interrogated and jailed before trials.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Officials convened three tribunals: one at Destrehan Plantation in St.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] John the Baptist Parish, and the third in New Orleans (Orleans Parish).
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] The Destrehan trials, overseen by Judge Pierre Bauchet St.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Martin, resulted in the execution of 18 of 21 captured people by firing squad.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Some slaves testified against others, but others refused to testify or submit to the all-planter tribunal.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] In New Orleans, Commodore Shaw presumed that "but few of those who have been taken were acquitted." The New Orleans trials resulted in the conviction and summary executions of 11 more slaves.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Three were publicly hanged in the *Place d'Armes*, now Jackson Square.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] One of those spared was a 13-year-old boy, who was ordered to witness another man's death and then received 30 lashes.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Another escaped person was treated with leniency because his uncle turned him in and begged for mercy.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] The sentence of a third person was commuted because of the valuable information he had given.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] The heads of those executed were put on pikes and the mutilated bodies of dead rebels displayed to intimidate other slaves.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] The naval officer Samuel Hambleton described the heads posted on stakes that lined the levee as follows, "They were brung up here for the sake of their Heads, which decorate our Levee, all the way up the coast.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] U.S. territorial law provided no appeal from a parish court's ruling, even in cases involving imposition of a death sentence on a slave.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] In fact, Claiborne did commute two death sentences, those of Henry and Theodore, each referred by the Orleans Parish court.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] No record has been found of any referral from the court in St.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Charles Parish, or of any refusal by the governor of an application for clemency.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Militias killed about 95 slaves between the battle, subsequent summary apprehensions and executions, as well as by execution after trials.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] From the trial records, most of the leaders appeared to have been mixed-race Creoles or mulattoes, although numerous slaves were native-born Africans.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Fifty-six of the slaves captured on January 10 and involved in the revolt were returned to their masters, who may have punished them but wanted their valuable laborers back to work.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Thirty more escaping slaves were captured and returned to their masters after planters determined they had been forced to join the revolt by Deslondes and his men.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] The heirs of Meuillon petitioned the legislature for permission to free the mulatto slave Bazile, who had worked to preserve his master's plantation.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Not all the slaves supported insurrection, knowing the trouble it could bring and not wanting to see their homes and communities destroyed.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] The uprising was short-lived and quickly crushed by local authorities.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Showing planter influence, the legislature of the Territory of Orleans approved compensation of $300 to planters for each escaping slave killed or executed.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] The territory gratefully accepted the presence of U.S. troops after the revolt.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] The national press covered the insurrection, with some Northerners seeing it arising out of the wrongs suffered under slavery.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Since 1995, the African American History Alliance of Louisiana has led an annual commemoration at Norco in January, where they have been joined by some descendants of members of the revolt.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] While the Destrehan Plantation tour concentrates on architecture and white lifestyle and family histories, a small museum in a converted slave cabin (not on the standard tour) features folk paintings of the 1811 uprising.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] More recently, the Whitney Plantation, in St.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] John the Baptist Parish, opened in 2014 and is the first plantation museum in the country dedicated to the slave experience.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] The Whitney Plantation includes a memorial and information to commemorate the 1811 Slave Uprising of the German Coast.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] In 2015, artist Dread Scott began organizing a massive re-enactment of the uprising; the 26 mile, 2-day event took place in November 2019.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] The uprising is featured in Talene Monahon's 2020 play about historical reenactment, *How to Load a Musket*.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] In 2021, the 1811 Kid Ory Historic House opened on the site of Woodland Plantation in LaPlace, which is in the National Register of Historic Places of the United States.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] The museum is dedicated to the German Coast uprising and to Kid Ory, an American jazz composer, trombonist, and bandleader born there in 1886.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The **Fiji Expedition of 1840** was an exploring and surveying expedition, which itself was a part of the wider United States Exploring Expedition (a.k.a. the **Wilkes expedition** or the **U.S.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Ex.**) that occurred from May 4 to August 11, 1840.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] It produced several scientific and cultural breakthroughs in realms such as cartography, oceanography, volcanology, anthropology, ethnography, ethnology, philology, linguistics, geology, taxonomy, trade, diplomacy, toponymy, epidemiology, pathology and Christian missionary work.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] It also was known for two separate punitive expeditions against separate groups of Fijians.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Ex. under the command of Lieutenant Charles Wilkes had just discovered that Antarctica was a continent, and finished surveying Wilkes Land.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] However, Wilkes was facing a significant deadline.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes was originally given a deadline of 3 years to conduct the necessary research for all the allotted study location goals for the expedition.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Unfortunately for him he only had two months to conduct the studies for Fiji expedition, then he would immediately have to journey to the Columbia river expeditions to finish the rest of the studies for the rest of the year.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] If Wilkes did not, the sailors' and marines' enlistment service would expire, and the expedition's future would have been put in jeopardy.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] This situation put Wilkes under immense pressure.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] As it was, besides the Columbia river expedition, the Fiji expedition was considered the most paramount research destination for several reasons.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] New England merchants and whalers frequented Fiji for its whale and sandalwood, and competed with the British and the French for the bêche-de-mer populations to sell in China.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] However, Fiji possessed many uncharted reefs, rocks, and currents, with a culture well known for its cannibalism (in fact for a while Fiji was also known as the Cannibal Isles) and a noted penchant for dragging boats to shore and killing all on board.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] No dependable navigation charts existed, and in the 12 years prior to 1840, 8 ships (5 of them being American) had been destroyed in the area.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] These conditions made travel to and around these Islands so precarious, the East India Marine Society of Salem, Massachusetts, United States had petitioned the federal government for local charts for sailors navigating these waters.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Although surveying was the primary reason for the Ex.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Ex. also brought along a group of scientists which were also deployed for the Fiji expedition.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Now that the Antarctic discoveries were finished, Wilkes' fleet traveled to Sydney, Australia, then to the Bay of Islands, New Zealand, and finally they rendezvoused at Tongatapu, in Tonga, and prepared for their next mission in Fiji.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes had already had his four ships refitted at Sydney.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] His current fleet at the time of the Fiji expedition consisted of Wilkes' flagship the USS *Vincennes* (sloop-of-war, 780 tons, 18 guns), the USS *Peacock* (sloop-of-war, 650 tons, 22 guns), the USS *Porpoise* (brig, 230 tons, 10 guns), and the USS *Flying Fish* (schooner, 96 tons, 2 guns).
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Furthermore, Wilkes had at least a dozen gigs, cutters, and whaleboats prepared for travel against the hazardous reefs.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes' fleet set sail out of Nukuʻalofa on May 4, 1840.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He dispatched the *Porpoise* under Lieutenant Cadwalader Ringgold to the Lau Group of the Fiji Islands, while the rest of the fleet went to the Koro Sea.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The 3 ships headed for the Island of Ovalau, but by the morning of May 7, the *Flying Fish* under the command of Lieutenant George Sinclair went missing, after it got caught on a reef.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes pressed on with the *Peacock* and the *Vincennes* and anchored by the village Levuka.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Upon Wilkes arrival, a white shipwrecked survivor of the Oneo a Nantucket man named David Whippey and one of his sons paddled up to the *Vincennes.* Whippey was what was called a beachcomber, which in this context meant a "tame white man" to the Fijians.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] This was a sort of mercenary, military advisor, and translator.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The earliest beachcomber Charlie Savage and those like him taught Fijians how to use fire arms.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] This revolutionized Fijian warfare, and they were greatly valued by war chiefs, who rewarded them with riches and women.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Whippey had risen to the title of "Mata-ki-Bau" (the Royal Messenger of Bau village.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes arranged for Whippey to have him meet the chief or "Tu'i" of Levuku.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes bestowed several gifts upon the chief, who in gratitude and with Whippey's aid sent a message to Tanoa high King *Vunivalu* of Bau (called "Old Snuff by the local whites) and head of the notorious Lasakau sea warriors, and asked to meet with him.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] After a messenger was sent, Whippey took Wilkes and 25 of his officers and naturalists (including the commander of the *Peacock* Lieutenant William L.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Hudson and Navy Geographer and passed midshipman Henry Eld), along with an entourage of natives, on a tour and hike of Mount Nadelaiovalau.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] At the top of the mountain Wilkes and his scientists could clearly see the surrounding area including nearby reefs and other nearby landmarks.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The group set out right away making charts, sketches, measurements for recording, and collecting plant and animal specimens.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] On May 8 Wilkes deployed two surveying parties on boats.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] One was to be led by Lieutenant James Alden Jr. who would leave Ovalau to explore the northern shore of Viti Levu Island.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The second boat was led by Lieutenant George F.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Emmons, who in turn scouted the south shore.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes gave the officer further orders that after exploring their respective shores that they should assemble at the Island of Malolo which was to the west of Viti Levu.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] That same day Lieutenant Sinclair arrived with the *Flying Fish* at Levuka and reported to Wilkes.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] On May 11 Wilkes decided to build an observatory of tents, houses, and a small research garden.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] It was situated 30 feet above the beach on a peak near Levuku village, and above Vi Tonga village as a forward operating center for the Fiji Expedition.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The observatory was erected on May 11, with guards surrounding the perimeter.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] On May 12, Chief Tanoa arrived in a finely decorated 100 foot, double hulled, outrigger canoe with a sail and a 40-man crew.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He boarded the Vincennes and through Whippey was able to negotiate a trade deal between Bau and the United States.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] A few days later, Wilkes received Seru Epenisa Cakobau the son and crown prince of Tanoa, who further cemented bonds of the Bau nation and the expedition.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Seru would one day come to unite the Kingdoms of Bau, Rewa, and Naitasiri into the short lived Kingdom of Fiji.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] While Tanoa was the King of Bau, he exercised the greatest influence among all the other kingdoms of the islands of Fiji, Tui Levuku was in charge of Ovalau Island.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] With the aid of Whippey, Tui Levuku helped the Americans maintain their supply lines, trade with Levuku village, and receive information through the first six weeks of the Fiji expedition.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] After a few says an Irish beachcomber named Paddy O'Connell entered Wilkes, tent on Ovalu.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] O'Connell attempted to hire himself out to Wilkes, but Wilkes dismissed him at first.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] However, a single story caught his interest.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] O'Connell informed Wiles that he was a witness to the murder of several of the crew of the American bêche-de-mer merchant ship the *Charles Doggett* in August 1834, on Ono Island.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes learned that a Fijian chief named Veidovi was the man who organized the attack.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] According to O'Connell he was a crewman of the *Charles Doggett* when the incident occurred.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] In this instance Captain Bachelor of the *Charles Doggett* made a contract with a chief named Veidovi for *bêche-de-mer* on Rewa.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] When the *Charles Doggett* reached Rewa, it was agreed that a minor chief would willingly be taken hostage for the protection of the Westerners while they set up a *bêche-de-mer* house on shore.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Later the chief feigned sickness and was allowed to return to shore.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The next day the minor chief returned with Veidovi and some of his men and asked for medicine at the *bêche-de-mer* house.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The mate, eight other men, and a boy came ashore, all except one were killed, robbed, and the house was house set on fire.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The next day the captain, through O'Connell, was able to negotiate for all the bodies back except an African American crewmate whose body was eaten.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Later O'Connell became a beachcomber and discovered that while Veidovi was the primary perpetrator of this attack, the other chiefs of Rewa and especially Veidovi's kin endorsed the killings.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Upon hearing this story Wilkes became angry and sent O'Connell to Lieutenant Hudson on the *Peacock* to arrest Veidovi.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] O'Connell met Hudson and gave him Wilkes' orders.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The pair of them set out for Rewa in Viti Levu where Veidovi lived.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] It was there that Hudson eventually met with King Kania or Roko Tui Dreketi/King of Rewa and Methodist missionaries of the English Wesleyan Mission who helped him get the lay of the land.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] After assessing the political landscape, Hudson quickly concocted a plan to trap Veidovi.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] On May 21 Hudson invited the King Kania and his three brothers on board the *Peacock* to a welcoming reception.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Between 70 and over 100 local Fijians showed up along with the Tui Dreketi himself, but Veidovi was noticeably absent.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Hudson lured the native royals into his cabin with an offering of a meal and then called for battle stations.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The royals were split away from their retainers.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Hudson promised mercy to the chiefs in exchange for them delivering Veidovi to them, and causing no harm to the local missionaries.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] After a spout of protest the King Kania agreed, and two of the chiefs brothers were released to arrest Veidovi dead or alive.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The following day Veidovi arrived and agreed to go quietly in exchange for the freedom of his family and their families respectively.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Hudson took Veidovi to his personal cabin for interrogation and Veidovi openly conceded to orchestrating the *Charles Doggett* killings.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Veidovi explained that he lured the mate of the ship into a trip and feigned a friendly greeting to the mate of the ship.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Then his men seized the mate and clubbed him to death, and then proceeded to kill more of the ship hands.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Veidovi added that his motivations were to acquire firearms and that he was only following his culture in that "...he had only followed the Fegee customs and done what his people had often done before.".
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Hudson decided to punish Veidovi by forcing him to travel with the Ex.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Ex. and then live in America for a few years, where he would learn to be civilized and not kill white people.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Veidovi was dismayed, since as a chief he had 55 wives and numerous children that he would have to leave behind.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Hudson then headed for Kadavu Island where it was said more of the perpetrators of the attack on the *Charles Doggett* resided.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] However, the wind was against him, and suffering for a lack of time in his other duties for the expedition, Hudson satisfied himself with the capture of Veidovi and returned to Levuka.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Word traveled fast of Veidovi's capture, it spread to the village of Levuka, and then to Wilkes himself.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Whippey and Tui Levuku soon caught wind of a plot to capture Wilkes in order to entice and exchange of prisoners (Wilkes for Veidovi).
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The suspected perpatrtors would have been King Tanoa who was allies with King Kania.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] In the Mountains of Ovalau resided the Livoni tribe who were allied with Tanoa.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes remained armed, furnished himself an escort, he ordered 40 men to reinforce the observatory.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes then took Seru hostage on board the *Vincennes*, repositioned the guns of the *Vincennes* to a more defensible position.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes also brought his dog Sydney with him (which terrified the natives), and an attempted kidnapping never materialized.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] In early June, a British expedition consisting of the HMS Sulphur (1826) HMS Starling (1829)) commanded by Captain Edward Belcher arrived in Fiji.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Belcher was conducting his own separate surveying expedition and had just come from the Vavaʻu island group in Tonga.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Belcher traveled to Rewa where the Sulphur had lost a rudder from hitting a reef.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] After Belcher's expedition encountered other members of the Ex.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Ex. and through messengers, Wilkes gave Belcher a spare rudder from the fleet.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Later, Wilkes came to meet Belcher aboard his ship, and they spoke together in Belcher's cabin.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] However, despite Wilkes' goodwill in offering Belcher an extra rudder, Belcher was less than pleased to see him.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Belcher was required to pay port charges due to the trade deal that he had set up between the U.S. and chief Tanoa.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The meeting did not accomplish much, although Wilkes found out that Belcher had explored the Columbia River the year before in 1839, and based on Belcher's descriptions Wilkes believed he would definitely need to extend the length of the Ex.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The two parted cordially and Belcher and his ships later sailed to Vanuatu.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Chief Tui Levuku decided to honor the Ex.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Ex. with a traditional Club dance/Meke called the Meke I Wau or Meke Mada on June 24 at Levuku village.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Over a hundred Fijians and their chiefs from Levuku and other nearby villages attended.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The Americans were directed to the Mbure/temple, or spirit-house, which had an elevated platform where they could more easily observe the festivities.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The location overlooked the village from where they observed a low square stone wall on the opposite end of the street.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] On one end many Fijians sat down awaiting the performance and on the opposite were several Fijian musicians.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Eventually a "Feejee Clown" emerged in the center of the crowd, and began to galivant and dance wildly, to the delight and laughter of all.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The clown's body was completely enveloped with green and brown leaves and several vines, except for his face to which he wore a mask.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes stated that to him the mask looked somewhat like the face of a bear.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The mask was painted black on one half and orange on the other.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The clown danced with one large club in one hand and a shorter one on the other.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] While the clown performed, the musicians began to play with hand claps, sticks, and bamboo joints which made a soft drumming sound.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Roughly 100 club dancers were waiting behind a rock until they were ready.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Then they emerged in a column of two and began to proceed down the street at a slow three step pace.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] They all wore the white *I-sala* turban typically worn by priests and chiefs as well as a white Masi tapa cloth to cover themselves.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Their sala were decorated with flowers and vines, and their faces were painted in various patterns of black and vermillion.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] As the dance columns advanced they split up from two columns to three and then to four and danced and swung their clubs in a variety of motions and poses.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] They danced into the square and joined the clown and the musicians.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The dancers began singing with the musicians and their dances became more rapid and volatile, before they concluded their song and dance with a loud cry of "Wha---hoo".
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] When the presentation had concluded the dancers laid their clubs down in a pile before the Americans as a gift to them, but they expected to receive gifts in return.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The next day Wilkes gave gifts on behalf of the expedition to Chief Tui Levuku so that he might distribute them.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Soon after the end of the club dance festival, Wilkes decided to pack up the observatory and move on to other areas of the Fijian Islands.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Before the expeditions departure the purser Robert Waldron purchased and donated land for the construction of a Methodist mission school, with both a school house and chapel led by John Hunt.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Following this, the *Vincennes* departed on the 28th of June, to survey the hot springs of Savusavu on the Island of Vanua Levu.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The *Peacock* had several accidents associated with or on it during this expedition.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] At Vita Levu the ship sustained considerable, but non fatal damages to its hull.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] While one of the Peacocks cutter boats had overturned and sank.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] At one point one man lost three fingers to an anchor chain.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] On another occasion a man accidentally shot off his index finger.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] A third sailor nearly had his leg entirely detached.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Later, another sailor had an accident while winding the capstan and broke his ribs.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] However, perhaps the worst accident occurred on June 29 when 2nd mate Joseph Baxter of the *bêche-de-mer* *Leonidas* unwittingly placed a gunpowder cartridge under his shirt while preparing to fire a cannon (for non offensive purposes).
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] A spark flew off from the igniter and hit the cartridge the man was carrying which exploded over three pounds of gunpowder, and the man was badly charred from the ordeal.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Baxter was later transferred to the Peacock for medical attention.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He confessed that he was a French man whose real name was Vincent Boudet.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] During one occasion of the expedition the *Peacock* was off the coast of Tavea when a chief and his wife and an escort of three canoes approached the ship.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Hoping to antagonize the crew, the natives explained that they had captured three prisoners from an enemy village and had "roasted them and eaten part!".
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] They displayed a piece of one of the bodies that had been preserved in plantain leaves to show the crew.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Then they produced a half gnawed on skull to be exhibited.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The crew also noticed one native eating an eyeball, with flesh dangling from his mouth.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Some of the men vomited at this spectacle.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Later the Waldron bought the skull to be added to the Ex.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Ex.'s artifact collection in exchange for some cloth.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] William Brackenridge the horticulturalist and Charles Pickering the naturalist teamed up to make several discoveries together while at Fiji.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] With their mutual cooperation, they discovered over 650 different plant species.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] This included a new species of tomato and poison ivy.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Moreover, Pickering made the discovery that if the science team did not bring anything that appeared valuable to the natives, they could travel about the Islands without great fear of danger or harassment.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] This gave them ample time an opportunity to conduct their research.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] And Brackenridge, for his part, found the last existing variant of sandalwood on Fiji, which up until that point was thought to have been extinct from over harvesting.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Horatio Hale, the teams' philologist and anthropologist, documented over 5,600 words in the Fiji language and documented their craftsmanship in producing various canoes, dwellings, and pottery.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] James Dwight Dana the team's geologist made a titanic discovery in his field.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He proved Charles Darwin's theory of subsidence, which Darwin had spoken about publicly, but was formally addressed in his book *The Structure and Distribution of Coral Reefs*.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] In the theory of subsidence after a volcanic Island is formed and after a lengthy period of time a fringing reef forms along the edges or "fringes" of the Island.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] After that and given more time the Island begins to erode and sink and a lagoon begins to form around the island and the fringing reef becomes a barrier reef.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Then after further erosion and sinking over time the island sinks into the sea and only the reef and lagoon it forms remains becoming an atoll.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Darwin at first thought he could not adequately prove his theory, but Dana proved it by finding all 3 stages of reef formations on the islands of Cicia, Matuku, and Nanuku.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Ex.'s surgeons was able to study a number of local diseases endemic to Fiji on Ovalau, as well as the natives methods for treating them.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] One of these diseases included a disease the Fijians of the time called "dthoke" which has similarities to both lupus and yaws, and may be mistaken for secondary stage syphilis.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Another was a Fijian form of influenza called the "dandy cough" that the natives believe spread and mutated through contact with contact from white people, or as the Fijian's called them "Papalangi".
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Fox believed this influenza may have come from an influenza epidemic that had spread in the USA a few years before the Ex.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Fox recorded reports from many local whites that about a tenth of the Fijian population had died during that time.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] On July 11th, the *Vincenees*, *Flying Fish*, and *Peacock* were surveying in Bua Bay, Bua, Vanua Levu.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes dispatched, Lieutenant Oliver Hazard Perry Jr.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] (of the Perry Family) and passed midshipman Samuel R.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Knox 20 miles southeast, to lead a two cutter survey to chart Solevu bay.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The pair and their crews had been stuck in the bay by a storm for numerous days, with dwindling supplies.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] While the boats were anchored a group of natives taunted them threateningly from the beach.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Eventually their food ran out and both Perry and Knox felt compelled to escape.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The winds blew hard as the crew made for the shore.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Upon disembarking the boat, the sailors were encircled by several natives with clubs, spears, and a small amount of firearms.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The crews gunpowder was wet and so if it came down to a fight the crew would need to resort to hand-to-hand combat.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] However, in an unprecedented move by Western accounts the chief in charge of the natives took pity on the explorers.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Knox and his men swam back to Perry's boat, which became overloaded.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] As night fell, the natives lit fires on the beach and occasionally took pot shots at Perry and his men.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] In the cover of night, the natives stealthily began diving and swimming to the boat, and attempted to either lift the anchor or cut the anchor chain to drag the boat ashore.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The sailors began firing into the water, and eventually were able to capture two of the tribesmen who swam to the boat and made an effort to appear to be allies.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Perry suspected them as spies and so arrested them.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] It turned out they were both chiefs one of high rank and one of low rank.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Upon taking these men hostage, the natives on the shore made no more attempts to go after the boat that night.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] It was supposed that they feared the death of their chiefs.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] When morning came Perry made a second attempt to escape the bay.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] This time he attempted to maneuver his cutter around the shallow reefs and into the open ocean.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The Natives, realizing what Perry was attempting to accomplish, assembled around the edges of the reef.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] At one point the boat struck a reef and took on water.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The men attempted to bail and keep their distance from the natives.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Perry was able to escape with his crew and prisoners.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] On July 12, Perry met with the *Vincennes*, *Flying Fish*, and *Peacock* which had all rendezvoused at Bua Bay.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] After learning what had happened, Wilkes assembled 11 boats, 80 men, and the *Flying Fis*h to exact retribution, and retrieve the stolen cutter.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The flotilla arrived in the afternoon at low tide.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] As the waters were shallow a mudflat had formed between Wilkes' ships and the stolen cutter.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes met with the chiefs representatives and used Whippey as a translator.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes commanded the natives to return the boat and all items that were in it.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The natives were intimidated as up until this point in Fijian history there was never before a time when so many westerners had gathered threatening war.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The chief returned the boat, but did not return the boats equipment and belongings of the crew.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Outraged Wilkes landed most of his men armed with muskets, but remained on a gig from which he would direct a Congreve rocket.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes ordered the burning of Solevu village and the politically linked nearby village of Tye.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Combined the fighters of these villages were between 150 and 200 warriors.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] However, both the warriors and the populace fled into the hills and Wilkes fired rockets into the village.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The villages were destroyed, but due to the simplicity of the villages' material, the structures would be repaired in a few weeks.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Aside from loss or damage to property no side suffered any casualties.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Following the burning of the villages, and in an act of good will, Wilkes released the two captured chiefs and bestowed them with valuable gifts.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] His logic was that they came bearing friendship and aid to Perry's crew.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] This was also done to demonstrate to the natives that hostility to Americans (and white people in general) would be met with vengeance, and cordiality met with reward.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Ex. soon moved on from Solevu to the Mamanuca Islands to continue their survey mission, while the Vincennes and Peacock deployed to Muthuata Island.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Whippey informed Wilkes that this set of islands was particularly notorious for being perilous to westerners, as the residents of Malolo were noted for being pirates and the worst offenders of attacking foreigners.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes acknowledged the danger and made sure his boats were grouped together and well escorted.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He deployed three boats and the *Porpoise* and *Flying Fish* for this mission.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The boats were led by Lieutenants Alden, Emmons, and Joseph Underwood.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] On July 22 the squadron reached Drawaqa Island at the southern most end of the Yasawa Islands.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He sent two boats led by Alden and Underwood to the middle of the Mamanucas, the *Porpoise* took the Western side, and the *Flying Fish* and Emmons' cutter took the Western end.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The goal was for all three groups to complete their surveying that day and then assemble together at Malolo Island the next day.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] On July 24, Alden and Underwood finished their surveying without issue, and anchored on the east side of Malolo next to Malolo Lailai for the night.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] In the morning Underwood and Alden noticed the *Flying Fish* and Emmons boat anchored in the distant East along Malolo.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] An hour later, Emmons boat approached Underwood and Alden's.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] They inquired for food, but Emmons regrettably told them that the *Flying Fish* was entirely bereft of anymore supplies.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] This distressed the officers as only a few days ago Wilkes had cut the food rations by a third due to low provision levels, and currently Underwood and Alden's men only had a few yams with them.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] It was decided to try and trade with the local natives for food.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Underwood encountered a Fijian boy chief in the area, who was carrying war clubs which struck him as menacing, and so arrested him.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Later, he found a group of local natives and through a Māori interpreter named John Sac, Underwood negotiated for food.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Underwood was able to negotiate a tentative deal between himself and the natives.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The village of Malolo was on the Southwest part of the island and the natives proposed making an exchange for a few hogs.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] However, in order to get them Underwood would have to accompany the natives and one of the boats would have to sail to the Southwestern part of the island to pick them up.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] It turned out that the local chief's son was the man that Underwood had captured.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] In light of this, Underwood agreed to travel with the natives to their village provided that the chiefs son stay with his boat as a captive and guarantee of Underwood's safety, and would be released when business was concluded.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Underwood used his own boat (the *Leopard*) as it was smaller than Alden and Emmons cutters and could more easily go over the shallows without getting trapped.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He left all but three of his muskets with the *Porpoise* in order to further reduce weight and increase the ease of travel.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] This was actually against the standing orders that Wilkes had laid out for safety, but Underwood did not believe that the Fijians were as dangerous as was commonly supposed.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Underwood brought Sac with him to translate, along with six other men.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The rest of the men stayed with the *Leopard* (commanded by Alden) and their hostage on the beach.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Underwood met a group of natives near the village by a tree.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The tree had many throwing and maiming clubs tied to the branches, and two thin hogs next to it.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Underwood tried to barter for the swine, but he was informed that no transaction could be made without the chiefs approval.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] After half an hour the chief appeared after returning from a fishing trip.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The Chief demanded a musket with ammo and powder in exchange for the hogs.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Meanwhile, Alden and his men had waited in their boat a short distance from the shore, however their men were becoming agitated.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The tide was coming in and Alden didn't trust the natives as much as Underwood did.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] A messenger soon came from Underwood giving him an update of the situation.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Alden sent a message to Underwood to stop negotiating and return to the ship.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He sent Wilkes' Nephew Midshipman Wilkes Henry (who was named after his Uncle), to deliver the message.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Soon after, a Canoe came up alongside the *Leopard* and began talking to the chief's son.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The Fijian attempted to get out of the boat, but Aden pulled him down.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Another half an hour passed, and negotiations seemed to be progressing.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Another messenger from Underwood informed Alden that the chief wanted a hatchet and then the hogs would go to the sailors.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Alden gave the man the hatchet and he ran to give it to Underwood.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Not long after Emmons arrived in one of the cutters.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He and his crew had been looking for an area to eat the pigs at the nearby Malolo Lailai island, and began discussing it with Alden.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Alden was sharing with Emmons his anxieties over the negotiations and the chief's son's attempted escape, when the native leaped out of the boat and made for the opposite direction from the village.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Alden ordered one of his men to shoot over the chief's head to entice him to return.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Accounts differ as to what happened next, however when the shot went off.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Alden and Emmons claimed that the chief's son's escape attempt was a signal for the natives to attack.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] While those who were negotiating with the chief claimed that the attack began after the shot was fired.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Either way, the chief shouted that he thought that the sailors on the beach had killed his son, and ordered an assault.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Two Fijians grabbed the musket of one of Underwood's men, named Joseph Clark.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Clark gripped the musket and then brandished a knife.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He stabbed one native and then bashed another with the muskets' shoulder stock.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Then, several natives began spilling out of the mangrove bushes.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Underwood's men began to fire their muskets as they retreated to the two boats.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] About 100 natives began to give chase to the men retreating on the beach and threw spears and throwing clubs at their enemy.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes Henry and Underwood covered the retreat.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Henry was hit by a club and then shot the man who threw it at him.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Then another native hit him in the back of the head.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Henry collapsed to the ground with his face in the water, was surrounded by natives, and then stripped.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Joseph Clark was hit by a glancing blow in the mouth and the spear landed in Underwood's left arm.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Clark shot the man who threw the spear in the head and then another native knocked Clark out with a club.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He fell into the water, but the pain from the salt water on his bloody face soon woke him.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Clark stood up and witnessed Underwood being clubbed in the back of the head.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Clark attempted to drag Underwood to safety with one arm, and hit away other natives with his other.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Then Clark was hit twice more and fell down.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He got back up when he noticed another native was about to club the unconscious Underwood and stabbed him repeatedly.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Clark grabbed Underwood again who briefly came to and told him to tell his wife he loved her.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Then Underwood had his head clubbed in and died.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Clark was left in a state of shock and delirium.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He got up and limped to the rest of the escaping sailors.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Clark's face was covered in blood and dangling flesh and in his absent minded state, he laughed and sang at the natives.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The natives were perplexed by Clark's actions and stayed clear of him for the rest of the engagement.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Besides Clark, all the men who retreated back to the beach that survived suffered injuries.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] When Aldan and Emmons saw the fighting on the beach their crews began to row for the shore.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Once the other retreating men had assembled at the boats with Alden and Emmons, Alden a handful of men went back to look for Underwood and Henry.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] They encountered Clark in his delusional state and sent him back to the boats.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The natives had retreated back to their village.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Then Alden and his men found the bodies of both of Underwood and Henry almost completely naked.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Underwood's face was smashed beyond recognition.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] As for Henry, aside from the bruising and his nudity, Henry looked unharmed, but his mourners soon realized that Henry had drowned while unconscious.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] On the beach, there lay the bodies of ten Fijians from the attack.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] One of them stirred and was still alive, and in a fit of fury and vengeance the men, shot and stabbed him several times, before cutting off his head.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] A number of the men, wanted to pursue the natives back to their village.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] But there were less than two dozen men, and the natives could return at any moment and overwhelm them.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Alden commanded the men make a swift retreat back to the rest of the expedition.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The bodies of Henry and Underwood were gingerly placed in the cutter and covered in jackets to uphold their dignity, and the two boats sailed back to the *Flying Fish*.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Once the bodies were brought on board they were placed in the ships port side and covered with a tarp.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The cadavers were stitched into hammocks, draped in flags, buried on a nearby small island, and hidden out of fear that the natives would dig up and cannibalize the bodies.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes named the Island Henry Island after his Nephew (not to be confused with Henry Island (Washington), which he also named after his Nephew later in the expedition).
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] That night (July 24) Wilkes set up boat patrols commanded by Alden, Emmons, and Eld around Malolo to ensure no native escaped.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] It became evident that the natives also expected a counterattack.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Fijians in full war paint and equipped with muskets were scattered around the shoreline and would fire pot shots at the boat crews.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The crews would occasionally fire back, but the natives would take cover and drop prone before a musket ball could hit them.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes sent a force of about 70 men and a Fijian scout in 3 divisions.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The force was commanded by Lieutenant Ringgold, they landed in Southern Malolo.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes gave orders to kill all men and burn the village, but "spare only the women and the children.".
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] From there the men began marching to the fortified village of Sualib just outside of where Underwood and Henry were killed.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The *Flying Fish* and *Porpoise* waited on the coast with their cannons fixed on the shore.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The *Flying Fish* was originally going to lead the boats into battle, but it grounded on a sandbar.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] In the meantime Wilkes organized a small fleet of boats commanded by Alden, Emmons, and Clark whose mission was to search and destroy all hostile escaping canoes.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] There other objective was to approach the smaller Arro (sometimes called Yaro) village and neutralize it while Ringgold's force would destroy Sualib and link up with Wilkes flotilla in Arro.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] As the landing party was disembarking, three canoes appeared and were headed to Malolo Lailai.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Emmons and Alden took two boats and pursued them.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Once they were close enough an interpreter asked the natives where they were from.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] A native responded that they were from Malolo.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Emmons fired the forward mounted blunderbuss and killed six natives.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The rest of the natives jumped in the water.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Alden ordered that the rest be taken as prisoners, but his men had bloodlust and shouted "Kill" repeatedly.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] One man grabbed a Fijian woman by the hair and was about to slash her with his sword when Alden aimed his pistol at him.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Alden was able to reign in his men and together with Emmons, and they captured several men, women, and children, including a chief from Arro village.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The men were handcuffed and kept captive, but the women and children were released on the beach.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] While Emmons and Alden were occupied capturing the natives during their engagement, Wilkes proceeded with his boats to Arro.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He found the village deserted, and put it to the flame.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The men had gone ahead to join the defense of Sualib and the women and children had fled to the mountains.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes continued on and hoped to reinforce Ringgold at Sualib, but found it destroyed.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He doubled back and later met Ringgold at Arro.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The ground force landed at 10 A.M. and divided up in to three groups as Wilkes had ordered.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The groups were led by Lieutenants Ringgold, Robert Johnson and Andrew Murray, and included passed midshipman Henry Eld and Alfred Thomas Agate of the science corps.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Ringgold gave a short speech and reminded the men to destroy everything except the women and children.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The forces split up into different paths and destroyed farms along the way, before meeting up and surrounded the fort.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The fort itself was circular, with a 12 foot wide by 6 feet deep ditch/dry moat which they used as a trench, and a ten foot tall coconut tree and whicker palisade on all sides.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The natives had occupied the trench and the palisade edges, and together they either aimed their muskets outside of the trench through small holes in the palisade walls.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] A number of chiefs, recognizable by their white headdresses, commanded the warriors in between the trenches and stockade.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The warriors began to shout obscenities at the oncoming attackers.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The Americans fired a Congreve rocket and their muskets at the fort, and the Fijians quickly dashed into the fort.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The enemy retreated, a portion of Johnson's division, without orders stormed the fort.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The attack was spearheaded by Sinclair with a double barrel shotgun.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] When Sinclair entered the fort he quickly realized that it was a trap.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The ditch which had been built outside of the palisades also extended into the interior and was occupied by a large number of natives.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] This included women armed with bows who fought with their men.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Retreat for Sinclair and his advance was impractical and decidedly more dangerous than it was worth.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The fort was purposefully built like a fish weir trap, with a wide opening, but a narrow avenue of escape.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Sinclair got shot with an arrow in his lapel, but it only penetrated the fabric of his coat and not the skin.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Sinclair's fortune did not stop at his lapel.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The Americans began running up to the palisade and shooting into the village through the small holes the Fijians had previously been using.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Musket fire and Congreve rockets poured into Sualib.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Americans began trickling into the village, in twos, by a narrow bridge, through the gate, and into the fort following Sinclair's example.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] At one point Sinclair shot a chief with his pistol, which turned out to be the chief of Sualib.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Several natives carried the chiefs limp body to a nearby hut.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The battle crept on in a state of havoc for about 15–30 minutes before a Congreve rocket hit the top of a dry roof and caught fire.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] A native warrior got on to of the roof in an effort to remove the rocket before the fire spread, but he was shot down in a hail of bullets.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The fire proliferated and began to engulf the village.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The blaze forced the natives to flee the ditch and into American musket fire, which cut them down.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The resulting spectacle was pure pandemonium.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] A translator attempted to shout that the women and children would be allowed to escape.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Fire and gun smoke were everywhere, children were weeping, pigs were crying, the fire roared, the noise was ear splitting.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The Americans cheered their success and then fell back to a coconut grove, as the village burned.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] After a half an hour to an hour, the fires had settled to an approachable state, the Americans reentered the village.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] They soon discovered, that based on the remaining native supplies, the natives had expected a lengthy engagement.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The Americans found piles of hollowed out calabashes filled with water, burnt yams and charred pigs.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Discarded muskets, spears, and clubs littered the floor of the ditch.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The weapons were pilled up on a pyre and immolated.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] After searching the still standing huts, Underwood's bloody cap was discovered.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Out of the bodies only four or five survived being burnt to ashes including a little girl and the chief of Sualib.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The preservation of the chief's cadaver was soon ended, as with a streak of vengeance, the Americans threw his body into a burning house.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Evidence of the horror that had occurred before was still present to the senses of the Americans.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The treeline was pierced by misfired arrows.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The smoke filled the nostrils of the sailors and marines which took on the smell of burnt human flesh, as it approached the heavens in an otherwise blue sky.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] It was in this setting that the otherwise exhausted combatants decided to rest and refresh themselves on coconuts to quench their thirst.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] While the men drank, it was discovered that the most significant injury among them was a sailor who suffered a solitary gash on the leg from an arrow.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] After the brief respite, the force divided into the marching lines to the nearby village of Arro and burned several houses and farms along the way.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] It was suspected that most of the surviving villagers were hiding somewhere in the hills.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] However, they did encounter one native on the way who was instantly bayonetted multiple times to death.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Upon arriving there, they found that Arro had already been burned down by Wilkes and Alden.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Adding the bayoneted man as a casualty and counting the lowest and highest estimate, approximately 58 to about 88 Fijians had been killed between Arro and Sualib.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The last skirmish that occurred during the battle lasted throughout much of the day.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] After midday, Lieutenant Emmons had been tracking five canoes that had been spotted in the morning.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] They had escaped Malolo, and were hiding near Malolo Lailai.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Each canoe contained about eight fighters and their sides were reinforced to curb a potential attack.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Emmons was sailing his cutter which was, at this point, only at half its normal capacity.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He had only seven men under his command.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] In any case, Emmons made full sail and pulled up alongside the closest canoe.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Emmons fired the forward mounted blunderbuss and killed several natives.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Emmons and another sailor jumped in the canoe, as Emmons grappled with a spear throwing native, the sailor killed him with a hatchet.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] One canoe got away, but the natives in the other canoes jumped overboard.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] After they took the plunge, they were either shot, slashed, or axed by the Americans as they swam for the shallows.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Emmons sailed back to the *Porpoise* before midnight.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] In the morning it was discovered that the bodies of the natives killed by Emmons and his men were eaten by sharks.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The next day (July 25, 1840) Wilkes made plans with a declaration to lead a second engagement to kill "Every man on the Island", however an assembly of natives congregated on the beach near the *Flying Fish*.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes summoned an interpreter and together they sailed on a gig to shore.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] As Wilkes drew nearer the crowd dispersed, leaving behind a lone native woman to treat with Wilkes.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The native offered Wilkes some of Underwood and Henry's clothes, belongings, and a chicken as an offer of peace.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes retrieved the recovered items from his fallen crewmen, but refused the chicken.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes was under the impression that according to Fijian tradition, for a nation to be truly conquered the populace of that nation must be present to witness a peace declaration.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Instead Wilkes entreated to the woman, he and his men would meet on a hill in southern Malolo to discuss peace terms with the whole tribe.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] If however, the remaining chiefs and peoples of Malolo did not make an appearance, then Wilkes and his men would continue the onslaught.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Around noon, Wilkes and his men climbed the hill, which perfectly overlooked views of the sheer destruction yesterday had delivered.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Then, at approximately 4 P.M. a column of weeping natives (including 40 men) began to approach the hill.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] At first, the native would not go beyond the foot of the hill.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] However, Wilkes threatened to wipe them out if they did not climb the hill in an act of contrite submission.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The natives crawled on their hands and knees up the hill.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] An old native man approached Wilkes, spoke for Malolo.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He begged for mercy, and declared that his people would never attack white men again.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He admitted his people were conquered and had only about 80 surviving men left.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He also offered Wilkes two young native women in reparation.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes gave a speech through a translator about the power of "white" people and that if a similar attack ever happened again, then he would drive the people of Malolo to extinction.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] July 26, Wilkes and his men went to what was left of Arro village and had the people fill casks of water for his vessels.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] On the morning of July 27, the *Flying Fish* and *Porpoise* sailed off the coast of Arro and 70 natives loaded them with 3,000 gallons of water, 12 pigs, and 3,000 coconuts.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] That same day the natives retrieved Underwood's pocket watch which had melted in the fire, and Henry's glasses.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] On July 31, the *Flying Fish* and *Porpoise* returned to Bua bay where the rest of the fleet was working.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes privately blamed Alden and Underwood for the deaths of Henry and Underwood.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] In retaliation Wilkes had Underwood's possessions sold at an auction to much protest from the officers, and most notably midshipman James Blair who was the executor of Underwood's freshly written will just prior to the battle of Malolo.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes vindictive streak did not appear to end with Underwood.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes next turned his anger to chief Veidovi.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] From his capture up until the end of the expedition in Fiji, Hudson had been kind to Veidovi and even permitted him to go on deck and speak to the officers.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] However, Wilkes had Veidovi transferred from the *Peacock* to his flagship the *Vincennes*.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Now Wilkes kept Veidovi confined to quarters.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Moreover, Wilkes had the ships barber cut Vincennes hair.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] This mortified Veidovi, since his hair marked his status and was important in Fijian culture.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Ex. had ended Wilkes published a book called *Narrative of the United States Exploring Expedition* in 1844.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes in hindsight was mad at Alden for a number of perceived grievances.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] One of these grievances included the idea that Alden was responsible for the deaths of Underwood and Henry.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] And he wrote about this an his other grievances in his book.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Ex. left Fiji in August and set a course for more surveying and scientific work in Hawaii, before temporary splitting up the expedition to survey Hawaii and other islands in Polynesia such as modern day French Polynesia, the Cook Islands, and the Gilbert Islands.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Later, the expedition surveyed the Columbia River.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] On the return trip the expedition traveled to Wake Island, and returned by way of the Philippines, Borneo, Singapore, Polynesia, and the Cape of Good Hope, reaching New York on June 10, 1842.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] While on the surveying expedition for the Columbia river, Wilkes appeared to have loosened his enmity to Veidovi at one point.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] He began allowing him on the deck of the *Vincennes*.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] A few months later on July 4th 1841 Wilkes and his men landed on Vancouver Island and fired off two howitzers in celebration of the holiday.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] During this occasion Veidovi was allowed to walk on shore.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] The next year in June, 4th 1842 Veidovi died a few days after landing in New York (possibly from pulmonary tuberculosis), although the Washington Herald inaccurately asserted that Veidovi died from a lack of eating human meat.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Soon after Veidovi's death surgeons at the Brooklyn Naval Hospital removed Veidovi's head, pickled it, and then after a time the flesh was removed, and the skull was thereafter labeled Specimen 292 and was featured in the Smithsonian Institution, and became one of the most popular exhibits.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Soon after Wilkes' arrival in New York several court martials were organized for the entire Ex.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Wilkes had made many enemies in both the Navy, and the government.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] He was almost universally despised by his men for many of the actions he took during the expedition.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Other officers were charged with various crimes, but Wilkes was charged with 11, and his actions throughout the Ex.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Ex. were criticized in the defense of the other officers.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] For his actions during Fiji the Battle of Malolo, Wilkes was charged with illegally attacking the natives.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Wilkes justified his actions by stating "But I felt then as I do now, that the punishment was sufficient and effectual, while it was accompanied, as far as it could be, with mercy.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] However, even the most ardent of Wilkes detractors supported Wilkes on this matter.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Many of them indicated by their words and actions that they hated the natives for killing their friends and desired revenge.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] What's more, Wilkes was able to garner sympathy for the death of his nephew of which it was universally acknowledged that he loved dearly.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Ultimately Wilkes was cleared of all charges including his Fiji charges.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] The exception was that Wilkes was found guilty of illegally flogging marines and sailors in Hawaii after they refused to work when their enlistments were up.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] As a consequence, Wilkes was given a public reprimand.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] In 1843, a 22-foot cenotaph obelisk was built in Mount Auburn Cemetery in Cambridge Massachusetts to remember the officers who had fallen in the Ex.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] More specifically, the monument memorialized the loss of life in two separate events of the Ex.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] This included the loss of the USS *Sea Gull* (1838) a schooner that was Captained by Midshipman James W.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Reid with the help of Midshipman Frederick A.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] The *Sea Gull* was awaiting resupply from the USS *Relief* (1836), after which she was due to rendezvous with the rest of the fleet at Valparaíso, Chile.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] She was last spotted off Cape Horn at Midnight on 28 April 1839.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] After a while when the *Sea Gull* never returned the Ex.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] While one side of the obelisk commemorates the memory of the officers of the *Sea Gull*, another preserves the memory of Henry Wilkes and Joseph Underwood killed during the first day of the battle of Malolo.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] The Officers and Scientific Corps. of the expedition took up a collection for their fallen comrades by the end of the Ex.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Wilkes and his family desired that this monument should be constructed at a cemetery in Brooklyn, New York for the benefit of Henry's mother and sister who lived near by.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] However, in part due to spite over Wilkes' treatment of them the officers had the monument built in Cambridge close to Underwood's widow.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Specifically the Obelisk reads: "To the memory of Lieutenant Joseph A.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Underwood and Midshipman Wilkes Henry, U.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] This cenotaph is erected by their associates, the officers and scientific corps of the U.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] The Methodist missionary Reverend David Cargill reported to Hudson that because of the arrest of Veidovi, the other chiefs of Rewa became terrified at the prospect of harming white people.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] And that this show of strength served to aid in both Western trade and missionary work.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] For his political, translation, and informative aid in the expedition Wilkes made David Whippey the temporary consul of the United States in Fiji.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Later, a more formal consul named John B.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] However, with Wilkes' recommendation Secretary of State John C.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Calhoun appointed him to vice consul of Fiji.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Nancy Shoemaker, she theorizes the combination of the Fijians newfound fear of retribution for attacks against Westerners following the attacks of the Ex.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Ex.. combined with Whippey's new position of power provided a lasting impact on Fiji.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] In that vein of thought, Shoemaker points out that Whippey's new found power complemented his unofficial title as chief of the white men/beachcombers of Levuka and the Royal Messenger of Bau village.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] With this fusion of power came a desire for autonomy for both Whippey and the white beachcombers he represented.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Traditionally, the beachcombers were compelled to fight for whichever local chief had them under employment.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] However, when chief Cakobau of Bau called them up to aid in him waging war against Cakaudrove at Somosomo, the beachcombers refused.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] They claimed they wished to protect their property.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Cakobau became incensed, and was even more so after he lost the war against Cakaudrove.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] He feared that directly punishing Whippey and his beachcombers might bring down the wrath of the United States or another western power.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Instead his punishment of the beachcombers was indirect and subtle.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] He encouraged other tribes under his domain to steal the beachcombers polygamous wives.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] He later demanded greater tributes from them and sent arsonists to burn down their homes.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] The situation became exasperated when in 1843, the beachcombers refused to participate in the Bau–Rewa war.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] This time Cakobau exiled the whites and their mixed-race children to Bua and near the village of Solevu that was destroyed by the Ex.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] However, by 1849, Cakobau allowed the beachcombers to return to Levuka.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Trade in Levuka had suffered since the exile.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] The beachcombers were all to often, the most reliable middlemen traders for Fijians and the trade ships that came through Fiji.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] To Cakobau's dismay upon the beachcombers return they began to dominate all foreign trade to the exclusion of Cakobau and the Fijian people as a whole.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] The beachcombers under Whippey began defending themselves against small skirmishes or arsons as advanced by Cakobau.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] At this point beachcombers like Whippey, and their mixed families, had begun to transcend from being middleman minorities to autonomous settlers.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] The beachcombers at Levuka and elsewhere gradually made moves to separate themselves from the Fijian populace and became a semi independent military and trading power.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] The British would later capitalize upon this development, when they took ownership of it in 1874 and made Levuka its first capital.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] However, according to Shoemaker, it was the Ex.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Ex.'s precedent for protection and subsequent retaliation for harm against whites that began the beachcombers move towards autonomy and the later British take over of the islands.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Ex. taken as a whole led to several lasting scientific revelations, explorative discoveries, and historical preservations that continue to endure to today.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] The Fiji expeditions artifacts contributed to the earliest collections for the National Institute for the Promotion of Science, the precursor to what would become the Smithsonian Institution.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] In addition to the cannibalized skull and the skull of chief Veidovi, an assortment of Fijian weapons had been procured for future display at the institute.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Wilkes names the Ringgold Isles after Lieutenant Cadwalader Ringgold.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Numerous botanical samples were also obtained from Fiji and other lands the Ex.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Ex. surveyed, and were placed in the United States Botanic Garden or the Smithsonian Gardens.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Dried plant specimens comprised the core of what is now the **National Herbarium**, an herbarium curated by the Smithsonian Institution's National Museum of Natural History.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] The Fiji Expedition was also not without its merits, for its contributions to science.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] As mentioned previously, Horatio Hale documented 5,600 words in the Fiji language as well as other information of anthological and cultural importance.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Through his studies he produced the book *Ethnography and Philology* (1846), which is said to have laid the foundations of the ethnography of Polynesia, including Fiji.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] He is often cited as the Father of Polynesian ethnology.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Moreover, the scientists Charles Pickering, William Brackenridge, and William Rich, collectively brought over 50,000 specimens of 10,000 species.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] And of the 241 charts that were created during the Ex.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Ex. there was included the first ever complete chart of Fiji.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1855-fiji-expedition] In October 1855, the United States Navy sent a warship to Fiji during the civil war on the islands.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1855-fiji-expedition] They demanded compensation from Seru Epenisa Cakobau, the Vunivalu of Bau and self-proclaimed Tui Viti (King of Fiji), in response to the alleged arson attacks on the American commercial agent in Lautoka, Viti Levu.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1855-fiji-expedition] The initial incident that led to the American expedition was the burning in 1849 of the house owned by agent John Brown Williams when it was hit by cannon fire.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1855-fiji-expedition] A subsequent incident happened the same year as the expedition when, again, fire was to interrupt Williams's duties.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1855-fiji-expedition] Another accidental fire on Nukulau destroyed his store, and some Fijians looted it.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1855-fiji-expedition] Boutwell, was sent to monitor the unrest in October, and her crew landed multiple times to protect American interests.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1855-fiji-expedition] When Commander Boutwell heard of the incidents involving William's house and store, he demanded US$5,000 in compensation from King Cakobau.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1855-fiji-expedition] This initial claim was supplemented by further claims totalling $45,000.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1855-fiji-expedition] He gave the natives a deadline and threatened them with a landing party of marines and sailors to capture the king in the island's village if they failed to pay.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1855-fiji-expedition] Fijian warriors put up some resistance, one American service man was killed, and two were wounded.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1855-fiji-expedition] Ultimately the Adams's men were successful in routing a contingent of natives from Lautoka, but Cakobau and the survivors escaped capture.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1855-fiji-expedition] Cakobau's claim to be King of Fiji was by no means universally recognised by his fellow-chiefs who jealously guarded the independence of their fiefdoms.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1855-fiji-expedition] If he acknowledged the debt, he did not have sufficient funds to pay it, yet if he disclaimed it by saying that it fell under the jurisdiction of another chief, he would jeopardize his claim to the kingship, which he wanted foreign powers to recognise.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1855-fiji-expedition] He decided to bide his time, hoping that the Americans were only bluffing.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1855-fiji-expedition] An 1858 Fiji expedition, involving the crew of *Vandalia*, achieved clearer results, and the debt itself was not resolved until 1862.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1858-fiji-expedition] In 1858, the United States Navy launched an operation on the island of Waya in Fiji following the death of two American traders there.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1858-fiji-expedition] The Pacific Squadron executed a punitive expedition against the native warriors of Seru Epenisa Cakobau and defeated them in a pitched battle at the village of Somatti.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1858-fiji-expedition] In mid-1858, two American citizens on Waya were killed and cannibalized by the natives.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1858-fiji-expedition] When word of the incident reached the American consulate at Ovalau, the Pacific Squadron sent the *Vandalia*, and the sloop-of-war arrived on 2 October 1858.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1858-fiji-expedition] The *Vandalia'*s draft was not shallow enough to reach Waya, so Commander Sinclair chartered the schooner *Mechanic* and placed her under the command of veteran Lieutenant Charles Caldwell.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1858-fiji-expedition] A force of 10 marines, forty sailors and a 12-pounder howitzer were mustered for the landing on Waya.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1858-fiji-expedition] A few Fijian guides and three American merchant sailors also participated.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1858-fiji-expedition] One was Captain Josiah Knowles of the *Wild Wave*, a clipper ship wrecked off Oeno Island.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1858-fiji-expedition] Knowles and 40 others were marooned on the island until being rescued by *Vandalia* and taken to Fiji.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1858-fiji-expedition] The expedition left Ovalau on 6 October 1858 and sailed west around the northern end of the main island of Viti Levu to Waya.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1858-fiji-expedition] During their passage to the island, Lieutenant Caldwell's men heard many stories from towns and villages about the warriors of Waya.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1858-fiji-expedition] The Wayan chiefs responsible for the deaths of the two American traders also sent a letter: "Do you suppose we have killed the two white men for nothing?
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1858-fiji-expedition] No, we killed them and we have eaten them.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1858-fiji-expedition] We are great warriors, and we delight in war".
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1858-fiji-expedition] Caldwell later wrote, "...and woe to the members of any strange tribe that falls into their hands... to be clubbed to death and eaten is the only alternative for the captive.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1858-fiji-expedition] It is not a matter of surprise that the tribes along our route learned with feelings of satisfaction the nature of our expedition".
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1858-fiji-expedition] At 03:00 on 9 October, the Americans made a landing and marched inland toward the village of Somatti over tropical and mountainous terrain.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1858-fiji-expedition] While climbing through the mountains, the 12-pounder was destroyed and left behind when it fell 2,300 feet (700 m) down the side of a hill as the expedition tried to pull it up.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1858-fiji-expedition] The column reached Somatti in daytime, and over 300 native warriors were in front of the village for defense, clothed in white robes and armed with clubs, rocks, spears, bows, and some muskets.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1858-fiji-expedition] The Americans had swords and carbine rifles.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1858-fiji-expedition] Lieutenant Caldwell ordered a flanking maneuver on the left side of the mass of warriors.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1858-fiji-expedition] Routed, the natives dispersed themselves amongst the town or fled into the jungle.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1858-fiji-expedition] Bartlett, who led a group of sailors, sang "Red, White, and Blue" and let out three cheers before charging and capturing the village.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1858-fiji-expedition] The crew of the 12-pounder, with no gun to fire, took charge of burning the village, and over 115 huts were destroyed.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1858-fiji-expedition] Marines under Lieutenant Alan Ramsey, providing a rearguard for the sailors, repulsed a final Wayan attack from the jungle after they had regrouped.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1858-fiji-expedition] In all fourteen warriors, including the two chiefs, were counted dead after a fierce half-hour battle.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1858-fiji-expedition] Two marines survived their wounds by musketry, two sailors were hurt badly by rocks, one other marine was hit in the leg with an arrow, and a sailor from *Wild Wave* was hurt as well.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1858-fiji-expedition] After the battle the Americans took until 16 October to return to the coast where the *Mechanic* was waiting.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1858-fiji-expedition] They stopped at friendly Fijian fishing villages and spread the news of their victory.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1858-fiji-expedition] Caldwell noted that two ramrods and one bayonet were lost during the march, and a large amount of ammunition was used in battle.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1858-fiji-expedition] The lieutenant received much credit for the operation, considered one of the most impressive military campaigns launched by the United States in the South Pacific during the nineteenth century.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] A United States presidential election was held on November 6, 1860.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Republican Party ticket of Abraham Lincoln and Hannibal Hamlin emerged victorious.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In 1860, the United States was divided over the issue of slavery, and four major political parties had nominated candidates in the 1860 presidential election.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Incumbent president James Buchanan, a Democrat, did not seek re-election.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The anti-slavery Republican Party nominated Abraham Lincoln, who previously had been a one-term Whig Representative from Illinois, for president.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Its platform promised not to interfere with slavery in the states where it existed, but opposed its extension into the territories.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] A group of former Whigs and Know Nothings formed the Constitutional Union Party, which sought to avoid disunion by resolving divisions over slavery with some new compromise.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The 1860 Constitutional Union Convention put forward former Tennessee Senator John Bell for president.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] After the 1860 Democratic National Convention adjourned without agreeing on a nominee, a second convention nominated Illinois Senator Stephen A.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Douglas as the Northern Democratic presidential candidate.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Douglas's support for the concept of popular sovereignty, which called for each territory's settlers to decide the status of slavery within the territory, alienated many radical pro-slavery Southern Democrats.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] With President Buchanan's support, Southern Democrats held their own convention, nominating Vice President John C.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Lincoln received a majority in the Electoral College, with all his Electoral College votes coming from Northern states.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He prevailed in 18 states, won 180 electoral votes, and received 39.7 percent of the popular vote.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Douglas won the second-highest popular vote total, but won only the state of Missouri; he was the only candidate in the 1860 election to win electoral votes in both free and slave states.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Breckinridge won 11 states, finishing third in the popular vote, while Bell finished fourth in the popular vote and won the electoral votes of the states of Kentucky, Tennessee, and Virginia.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In the last presidential election in which it appointed its presidential electors at the discretion of the state legislature rather than by popular vote (and was the only state to do so), the presidential electors of South Carolina cast their ballots for Breckinridge.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The 1860 election was the first of six consecutive Republican presidential victories.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Lincoln's election as the first Republican president served as the main catalyst for Southern secession and the American Civil War.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] His election motivated seven Southern states, all of which had voted for Breckinridge, to secede from the United States before Lincoln's inauguration on March 4, 1861.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Civil War began less than two months after the inauguration with the Battle of Fort Sumter, after which four more slave states seceded.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The 1860 presidential election conventions were unusually tumultuous, particularly because a split in the Democratic Party had led to both Northern and Southern party conventions.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Republican National Convention met in mid-May 1860 after the Democrats had been forced to adjourn their convention in Charleston.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] With the Democrats in disarray and a sweep of the Northern states possible, the Republicans felt confident going into their convention in Chicago.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Seward from New York was considered the front-runner, followed by Salmon P.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Chase from Ohio, and Missouri's Edward Bates.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Abraham Lincoln from Illinois was less well-known and was not considered to have a good chance against Seward.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Seward had been governor and senator of New York, and was an able politician with a Whig background.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Clay, and Benjamin Wade, who might be able to win if the convention deadlocked.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] As the convention developed, however, it was revealed that frontrunners Seward, Chase, and Bates had each alienated factions of the Republican Party.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Seward had been painted as a radical, and his speeches on slavery predicted inevitable conflict, which spooked moderate delegates.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He also was firmly opposed to nativism, which further weakened his position.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He had also been abandoned by his longtime friend and political ally Horace Greeley, publisher of the influential *New-York Tribune*.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Chase, a former Democrat, had alienated many of the former Whigs by his coalition with the Democrats in the late 1840s.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He had also opposed tariffs demanded by Pennsylvania and even had opposition from his own delegation from Ohio.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Chase's firm anti-slavery stance made him popular with the Radical Republicans; but what he offered in policy, he lacked in charisma and political acumen.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The conservative Bates was an unlikely candidate but found support from Horace Greeley, who sought any chance to defeat Seward, with whom he now had a bitter feud.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He was not unknown; he had gained prominence in the 1858 Lincoln–Douglas debates and had represented Illinois in the House of Representatives.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Lincoln had been quietly eyeing a run since the debates, ensuring that they were widely published and that a biography of himself was published.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He gained great renown with his acclaimed February 1860 Cooper Union speech, which may have ensured him the nomination, even though he had not yet announced his intention to run.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Delivered in Seward's home state and attended by Greeley, Lincoln used the speech to show that the Republican Party was a party of moderates, not crazed fanatics, as Southerners and Democrats claimed.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Afterward, Lincoln was in much demand for speaking engagements.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] As the convention approached, Lincoln did not campaign actively, as the "office was expected to seek the man".
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] So it did at the Illinois state convention, a week before the national convention.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Young politician Richard Oglesby found several fence rails that Lincoln may have split as a youngster and paraded them into the convention with a banner that proclaimed Lincoln to be "The Rail Candidate" for president.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Lincoln received a thunderous ovation, surpassing his and his political allies' expectations.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Lincoln's campaign managers had printed and distributed thousands of fake convention admission tickets to Lincoln supporters to ensure and increase the crowd's support.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Even with such support from his home state, Lincoln faced a difficult task if he was to win the nomination.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He set about ensuring that he was the second choice of most delegates, realizing that the first round of voting at the convention was unlikely to produce a clear winner.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He engineered that the convention would be held in Chicago, which would be inherently friendly to the Illinois-based Lincoln.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He also made sure that the Illinois delegation would vote as a bloc for him.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Lincoln did not attend the convention in person and left the task of delegate wrangling to several close friends.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The first round of voting predictably produced a lead for Seward, but not a majority, with Lincoln in second place.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The second round eliminated most of the minor contenders, with voters switching mostly to Seward or Lincoln.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The convention remained deadlocked, however, and successful political maneuvering by Lincoln's delegates persuaded some delegates to abandon Seward in favor of Lincoln.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Lincoln's combination of a moderate stance on slavery, his position on economic issues, his western origins, and his strong oratory proved to be exactly what the delegates wanted in a president.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On the third ballot on May 18, Lincoln secured the presidential nomination overwhelmingly.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Senator Hannibal Hamlin from Maine was nominated for vice president, defeating Clay.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The party platform promised not to interfere with slavery in the states, but opposed slavery in the territories.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The platform promised tariffs protecting industry and workers, a Homestead Act granting free farmland in the West to settlers, and the funding of a transcontinental railroad.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] There was no mention of Mormonism (which had been condemned in the Party's 1856 platform), the Fugitive Slave Act, personal liberty laws, or the Dred Scott decision.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] While the Seward forces were disappointed at the nomination of a little-known western upstart, they rallied behind Lincoln, while abolitionists were angry at the selection of a moderate and had little faith in Lincoln.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Douglas from Illinois, James Guthrie from Kentucky, Robert Mercer Taliaferro Hunter from Virginia, Joseph Lane from Oregon, Daniel S.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Dickinson from New York, and Andrew Johnson from Tennessee, while three other candidates, Isaac Toucey from Connecticut, James Pearce from Maryland, and Jefferson Davis from Mississippi (the future president of the Confederate States) also received votes.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Douglas, a moderate on the slavery issue who favored "popular sovereignty", was ahead on the first ballot, but was 56½ votes short of securing the nomination.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On the 57th ballot, with Douglas still ahead, but 51½ votes short of the nomination, the exhausted and desperate delegates agreed on May 3 to cease voting and adjourn the convention.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] While some considered Horatio Seymour a compromise candidate for the national Democratic nomination at the reconvening convention in Baltimore, Seymour wrote a letter to the editor of his local newspaper declaring unreservedly that he was not a candidate for either spot on the ticket.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] After two ballots - the 59th ballot overall - the remaining Democrats nominated Stephen A.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The election would now pit Lincoln against his longtime political rival, whom Lincoln had lost to in the Illinois senate race just two years earlier.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] That two candidates were from Illinois showed the importance of the West in the election.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] While Benjamin Fitzpatrick from Alabama was nominated for vice president, he refused the nomination.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] After the convention concluded with no vice presidential nominee, Douglas offered the vice presidential nomination to Herschel V.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The southern delegates walked out of Institute Hall on April 30, moving at first to the Saint Andrews Hall, then to Military Hall on May 1st.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On May 3rd, when the northern delegates left Charleston, the southern delegates left as well, reconvening at Metropolitan Hall in Richmond, Virginia on June 11.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] When the Democrats reconvened at Front Street Theater in Baltimore, they rejoined (except South Carolina and Florida, who had stayed in Richmond).
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] When the convention seated two replacement delegations on June 18, they walked out again or boycotted the convention, accompanied by nearly all other Southern delegates and erstwhile Convention chair Caleb Cushing, a New Englander and former member of Franklin Pierce's cabinet.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This larger group met immediately in Baltimore's Maryland Institute Hall, with Cushing again presiding.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] They adopted the pro-slavery platform rejected at Charleston, and nominated Vice President John C.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Breckinridge for president, and Senator Joseph Lane from Oregon for vice president.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Yancey and some (less than half) of the bolters - almost entirely from the Lower South - met on June 28 at Metropolitan Hall in Richmond, along with the South Carolina and Florida delegations, at a convention that affirmed the nominations of Breckinridge and Lane.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Besides the Democratic parties in the Southern states, the Breckinridge/Lane ticket was also supported by the Buchanan administration.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Buchanan's own continued prestige in his home state of Pennsylvania ensured that Breckinridge would be the principal Democratic candidate in that populous state.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Breckinridge was the last sitting vice president nominated for president until Richard Nixon in 1960.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Constitutional Union Party was formed by remnants of both the defunct Know Nothing and Whig parties who were unwilling to join either the Republicans or the Democrats.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The new party's members hoped to stave off Southern secession by avoiding the slavery issue.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] They met in the Eastside District Courthouse of Baltimore and nominated John Bell from Tennessee for president over Governor Sam Houston of Texas on the second ballot.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Edward Everett was nominated for vice president at the convention on May 9, 1860, one week before Lincoln.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] John Bell was a former Whig who had opposed the Kansas–Nebraska Act and the Lecompton Constitution.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Edward Everett had been president of Harvard University and Secretary of State in the Millard Fillmore administration.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Radical Abolitionist Party was a remnant of the Liberty Party that formed after most former Liberty and Free Soil Party members joined the Republicans in the 1850s.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] A convention of one hundred delegates was held in Convention Hall, Syracuse, New York, on August 29, 1860.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Delegates were in attendance from New York, Pennsylvania, New Jersey, Michigan, Illinois, Ohio, Kentucky, and Massachusetts.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Gerrit Smith, a prominent abolitionist and the 1848 presidential nominee of the original Liberty Party, had sent a letter in which he stated that his health had been so poor that he had not been able to be away from home since 1858.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Nonetheless, he remained popular in the party because he had helped inspire some of John Brown's supporters at the Raid on Harpers Ferry.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In his letter, Smith donated $50 to pay for the printing of ballots in the various states.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] There was quite a spirited contest between the friends of Gerrit Smith and William Goodell in regard to the nomination for the presidency.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In spite of his professed ill health, Gerrit Smith was nominated for president and Samuel McFarland from Pennsylvania was nominated for vice president.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In Ohio, Illinois, and Indiana, slates of presidential electors pledged to Smith and McFarland ran with the name of the Union Party.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] They received a total of 176 votes in the general election, 0.004% of the total.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The People's Party was a loose association of the supporters of Governor Samuel Houston.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On April 20, 1860, the party held what it termed a national convention to nominate Houston for president on the San Jacinto Battlefield in Texas.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Houston's supporters at the gathering did not nominate a vice presidential candidate, since they expected later gatherings to carry out that function.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Later mass meetings were held in northern cities, such as New York City on May 30, 1860, but they too failed to nominate a vice presidential candidate.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Houston, never enthusiastic about running for the presidency, soon became convinced that he had no chance of winning and that his candidacy would only make it easier for the Republican candidate to win.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He withdrew from the race on August 16, and urged the formation of a Unified "Union" ticket in opposition to Lincoln.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In their campaigning, Bell and Douglas both claimed that disunion would not necessarily follow a Lincoln election.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Nonetheless, loyal army officers in Virginia, Kansas and South Carolina warned Lincoln of military preparations to the contrary.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Mexican War hero Winfield Scott suggested to Lincoln that he assume the powers of a commander-in-chief before inauguration.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] However, historian Bruce Chadwick observes that Lincoln and his advisors ignored the widespread alarms and threats of secession as mere election trickery.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Indeed, voting in the South was not as monolithic as the Electoral College map would make it seem.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Economically, culturally, and politically, the South was made up of three regions.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In the states of the Upper South, also known as the Border South (Delaware, Maryland, Kentucky, and Missouri), unionist popular votes were scattered among Lincoln, Douglas, and Bell, to form a majority in all four.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In the four Middle South states, there was a unionist majority divided between Douglas and Bell in Virginia and Tennessee; in North Carolina and Arkansas, the unionist (Bell and Douglas) vote approached a majority.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In three of the seven Deep South states, unionists (Bell and Douglas) won divided majorities in Georgia and Louisiana and neared it in Alabama.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Breckinridge convincingly carried only four of the seven states of the Deep South (South Carolina, Florida, Mississippi, and Texas).
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Deep South states had the largest enslaved populations, and consequently the smallest enfranchised free white populations.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Among the slave states, the three states with the highest voter turnouts voted the most one-sided.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Texas, with five percent of the total wartime South's population, voted 75 percent Breckinridge.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kentucky and Missouri, with one-fourth of the total population, voted 73 percent pro-Union Bell, Douglas and Lincoln.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In comparison, the other six states of the Deep South made up one-fourth of the Confederate voting population; this was split 57 percent for Breckinridge versus 43 percent for the two pro-union candidates.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The four states that were admitted to the Confederacy after Fort Sumter held almost half its population, and voted a narrow combined majority of 53 percent for the pro-union candidates.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In the eleven states that would later declare their secession from the Union and be controlled by Confederate armies, ballots for Lincoln were cast only in Virginia, where he received 1,929 votes (1.15 percent of the total).
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The vast majority of the votes Lincoln received were cast in border counties of what would soon become West Virginia – the future state accounted for 1,832 of Lincoln's 1,929 votes.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Lincoln received no votes at all in 121 of the state's at-the-time 145 counties (including 31 of the 50 that would form West Virginia), received a single vote in three counties and received ten or fewer votes in nine of the 24 counties where he polled votes.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Hancock County (Virginia's northernmost at the time) returned Lincoln's best result – he polled over 40% of the vote there and finished in second place (Lincoln polled only eight votes fewer than Breckinridge).
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Of the 97 votes cast for Lincoln in the state's post-1863 boundaries, 93 were polled in four counties along the Potomac River and four were tallied in the coastal city of Portsmouth.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Although Lincoln received no votes in 10 Southern states, this was not because he was removed from the ballot in those states, but rather due to the Republican Party's absence in those states (parties rather than states printed ballots in that era).
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] One key difference between modern elections and those of the mid-nineteenth century is that at the time the state did not print and distribute ballots.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Moreover, since voters did not choose the president directly, but rather presidential electors, the only way for a voter to meaningfully support a particular candidate for president was cast a ballot for citizens of his state who would have pledged to vote for the candidate in the Electoral College.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In ten southern slave states, no citizen would publicly pledge to vote for Abraham Lincoln, so citizens there had no legal means to vote for the Republican nominee.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In most of Virginia, no publisher would print ballots for Lincoln's pledged electors.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Of the four slave states that did not secede Lincoln came third in Delaware and fourth in Missouri, Kentucky and Maryland.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Within the fifteen slave states, Lincoln won only two counties out of 996, Missouri's St.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In the 1856 election, the Republican candidate for president had received no votes at all in twelve of the fourteen slave states with a popular vote (these being the same states as in the 1860 election, plus Missouri and Virginia).
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The election was held on Tuesday, November 6, 1860, and was noteworthy for the exaggerated sectionalism and voter enthusiasm in a country that was soon to dissolve into civil war.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Voter turnout was 81.2%, the highest in American history up to that time, and the second-highest overall (exceeded only in the election of 1876).
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] 31.5% of the voting age population voted.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Since Andrew Jackson had won re-election in 1832, all six subsequent presidents had only won one term, while the last four of those had won with a popular vote under 51 percent.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Lincoln won the Electoral College with less than 40 percent of the popular vote nationwide by carrying states above the Mason–Dixon line and north of the Ohio River, plus the states of California and Oregon in the Far West.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Unlike every preceding president-elect, Lincoln did not carry even one slave state; he instead carried all eighteen free states exclusively.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Lincoln received no votes in ten Southern states because the Republican Party was absent in those states (parties rather than states printed ballots in that era).
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] There were no ballots distributed for Lincoln in ten of the Southern states: Alabama, Arkansas, Florida, Georgia, Louisiana, Mississippi, North Carolina, South Carolina, Tennessee, and Texas.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This withheld 61 potential electoral votes from Lincoln, a fifth of what was the total 303 available to the other candidates.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In a similar divide between North and South electors, Breckenridge carried nine of the ten states that withheld Lincoln from the ballot, the exception being Tennessee.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] It should be further noted that, prior to the introduction of the secret ballot in the 1880s, the concept of ballot access did not exist in the sense it does today: there was no standardized state-issued ballot for a candidate to "appear" on.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Instead, presidential ballots were printed and distributed by agents of the candidates and their parties, who organized slates of would-be electors publicly pledged to vote for a particular candidate.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Lincoln won the second-lowest share of the popular vote among all winning presidential candidates in U.S. history.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Lincoln's share of the popular vote would likely have been even lower if there had been a popular vote in South Carolina, though conversely it would likely have been marginally higher had Republican ballots been widely available to voters throughout the Southern States.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Republican victory resulted from the concentration of votes in the free states, which together controlled a majority of the presidential electors.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Wide Awakes young Republican men's organization massively expanded registered voter lists, and population increases in the free states had far exceeded those seen in the slave states for many years before the election of 1860, hence free states dominated in the Electoral College.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Gasconade County, Missouri has voted for a Republican presidential candidate in every election from 1860 on, which, as of 2024, makes it the longest Republican winning streak in presidential elections in the nation.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Despite Lincoln's commanding victory, this was the first election in American history in which the winner failed to win a majority of votes in his home county, with Lincoln narrowly losing Sangamon County, Illinois to Douglas, his main opponent in the North.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Regardless, Lincoln won absolute majorities (>50%) in enough states, that if he lost all states that he took with pluralities, he still would have received enough electoral votes to win.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In short, even if Ranked-Choice Voting, or any other runoff system had been in effect in every state, Lincoln still would have won on the first round.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In New York, Pennsylvania, and New Jersey, where anti-Lincoln votes were combined into fusion tickets, Lincoln still won New York and Pennsylvania and split New Jersey.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Nevertheless, a shift of 25,000 votes to the fusion ticket in New York would have left Lincoln with 145 electoral votes — seven votes short of winning the Electoral College — and forced a contingent election in the House of Representatives.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Alternatively, a shift of only 15,400 votes over California, Illinois, Minnesota, New Jersey, Oregon, and Rhode Island would have left Lincoln short of the necessary 152 electoral votes.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Of the five states that Lincoln failed to carry, he received 20 percent of the vote in only one (Delaware) and 10 percent of the vote in one more (Missouri).
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Like Lincoln, Breckinridge and Bell won no electoral votes outside of their respective sections.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] While Bell retired to his family business, quietly supporting his state's secession, Breckinridge served as a Confederate general.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He finished second in the Electoral College with 72 votes, carrying eleven of fifteen slave states (including South Carolina, whose electors were chosen by the state legislature, not popular vote).
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Breckinridge stood a distant third in national popular vote at eighteen percent, but accrued 50 to 75 percent in the first seven states that would form the Confederate States of America.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He took nine of the eleven states that eventually joined, plus the border slave states of Delaware and Maryland, losing only Virginia and Tennessee.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Breckinridge received very little support in the free states, showing some strength only in California, Oregon, Pennsylvania, and Connecticut.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bell carried three slave states (Tennessee, Kentucky, and Virginia) and lost Maryland by only 722 votes.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Nevertheless, he finished a remarkable second in all slave states won by Breckinridge or Douglas.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He won 45 to 47 percent in Maryland, Tennessee, and North Carolina and canvassed respectably with 36 to 40 percent in Missouri, Arkansas, Louisiana, Georgia, and Florida.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bell himself had hoped that he would take over the former support of the extinct Whig Party in free states, but the majority of this support went to Lincoln.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Thus, except for running mate Everett's home state of Massachusetts, and California, Bell received even less support in the free states than did Breckinridge, and consequently came in last in the national popular vote, at 12.62%.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Douglas was the only candidate who won electoral votes in both slave and free states (free New Jersey and slave Missouri).
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] His support was the most widespread geographically; he finished second behind Lincoln in the popular vote with 29.52%, but last in the Electoral College.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] His 12 electoral votes are the lowest for a Democrat in history.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Douglas attained a 28 to 47% share in the states of the Mid-Atlantic, Midwest, and Trans-Mississippi West, but slipped to 19 to 39% in New England.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Outside his regional section, Douglas took 15 to 17% of the popular vote total in the slave states of Kentucky, Alabama, and Louisiana, then 10 percent or less in the nine remaining slave states.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Douglas, in his "Norfolk Doctrine", reiterated in North Carolina, promised to keep the Union together by coercion if states proceeded to secede: the popular vote for Lincoln and Douglas combined was 69.17% of the turnout.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The 1860 Republican ticket was the first successful national ticket that did not feature a Southerner, and the election marked the end of Southern political dominance in the United States.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Between 1789 and 1860, Southerners had been president for two-thirds of the era, and had held the offices of Speaker of the House and President pro tempore of the Senate during much of that time.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Moreover, since 1791, Southerners had constituted a majority of the Supreme Court.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] (b) *The option of Lincoln was absent from 20.13% of ballots across ten states.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Lincoln's victory and imminent inauguration as president was the immediate cause for declarations of secession by seven Southern states (South Carolina, Mississippi, Florida, Alabama, Georgia, Louisiana, and Texas) from 20 December 1860 to 1 February 1861.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] They then formed the Confederate States of America.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] On 9 February 1861, Jefferson Davis was elected president of the Confederacy.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] All of the secessionist activity was motivated by fear for the institution of slavery in the South.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] If the President (and, by extension, the appointed federal officials in the South, such as district attorneys, marshals, postmasters, and judges) opposed slavery, it might collapse.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] There were fears that abolitionist agents would infiltrate the South and foment slave insurrections.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] (The noted secessionist William Lowndes Yancey, speaking at New York's Cooper Institute in October 1860, asserted that with abolitionists in power, "Emissaries will percolate between master [and] slave as water between the crevices of rocks underground.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] They will be found everywhere, with strychnine to put in our wells.") Less radical Southerners thought that with Northern antislavery dominance of the federal government, slavery would eventually be abolished, regardless of present constitutional limits.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Bertram Wyatt-Brown argues that secessionists desired independence as necessary for their honor.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] They could no longer tolerate Northern state attitudes that regarded slave ownership as a great sin and Northern politicians who insisted on stopping the spread of slavery.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Another bloc of Southerners resented Northern criticism of slavery and restrictions on slavery but opposed secession as dangerous and unnecessary.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] However, the "conditional Unionists" also hoped that when faced with secession, Northerners would stifle anti-slavery rhetoric and accept pro-slavery rules for the territories.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] It was that group that prevented immediate secession in Virginia, North Carolina, Tennessee, and Arkansas when Lincoln took office on March 4, 1861.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] He took no action against the secessionists in the seven "Confederate" states, but also declared that secession had no legal validity and refused to surrender federal property in those states.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] (He also reiterated his opposition to slavery anywhere in the territories.) Preparing to form an army, on 6 March 1861 Davis called for 100,000 volunteers to serve for twelve months.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The political standoff continued until mid-April, when Davis ordered Confederate troops to bombard and capture Fort Sumter.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Lincoln then called for troops to put down rebellion, which wiped out the possibility that the crisis could be resolved by compromise.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Nearly all "conditional Unionists" joined the secessionists, including for example presidential candidate John Bell of the Constitutional Union Party, whose home state of Tennessee was the last to secede.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The Virginia convention and the reconvened Arkansas convention both declared secession, as did the legislatures of Tennessee and North Carolina; all four states joined the Confederacy.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Missouri and Kentucky stayed in the United States, but had unrecognized dual governments.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] After the Civil War begun, Douglas then threw his support behind Lincoln and undertook a tour to bolster support for the Union, making visits to Virginia, Ohio and Illinois.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Douglas declared "There are no neutrals, only patriots and traitors".
[src:american-revolutionary-war/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] However, three months after Lincoln's inauguration, Douglas contracted typhoid fever and died in Chicago on June 3, 1861.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The conflict was fought in North America, the Caribbean, and the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The war's outcome seemed uncertain for most of the war, but Washington and the Continental Army's decisive victory in the Siege of Yorktown in 1781 led King George III and the Kingdom of Great Britain to negotiate an end to the war.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] In 1783, in the Treaty of Paris, the British monarchy acknowledged the independence of the Thirteen Colonies, leading to the establishment of the United States as an independent and sovereign nation.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] In 1763, after the British Empire gained dominance in North America following its victory over the French in the Seven Years' War, tensions and disputes began escalating between the British and the Thirteen Colonies, especially following passage of the Stamp and Townshend Acts.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The British Army responded by seeking to occupy Boston militarily, leading to the Boston Massacre on March 5, 1770.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] In mid-1774, with tensions escalating even further between the British Army and the colonies, the British Parliament imposed the Intolerable Acts, an attempt to disarm Americans, leading to the Battles of Lexington and Concord in April 1775, the first battles of the Revolutionary War.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] In June 1775, the Second Continental Congress voted to incorporate colonial-based Patriot militias into a central military, the Continental Army, and unanimously appointed Washington its commander-in-chief.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Two months later, in August 1775, George III declared the colonies to be in a state of rebellion.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] In July 1776, the Second Continental Congress formalized the war, passing the Lee Resolution on July 2, and, two days later, unanimously adopting the Declaration of Independence, on July 4.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] In March 1776, in an early win for the newly-formed Continental Army under Washington's command, following a successful siege of Boston, the Continental Army successfully drove the British Army out of Boston.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] British commander in chief William Howe responded by launching the New York and New Jersey campaign, which resulted in Howe's capture of New York City in November.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Washington responded by clandestinely crossing the Delaware River and winning small but significant victories at Trenton and Princeton.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] In the summer of 1777, as Howe was poised to capture Philadelphia, the Continental Congress fled to Baltimore.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] In October 1777, a separate northern British force under the command of John Burgoyne was forced to surrender at Saratoga in an American victory that proved crucial in convincing France and Spain that an independent United States was a viable possibility.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] France signed a commercial agreement with the revolutionaires, followed by a Treaty of Alliance in February 1778.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] In 1779, the Sullivan Expedition undertook a scorched earth campaign against British-allied factions of the Haudenosaunee Confederacy (*also* Iroquois).
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Native American raids on the American frontier, however, continued to be a problem.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Also, in 1779, Spain allied with France against Great Britain in the Treaty of Aranjuez, though Spain did not formally ally with the Americans.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Howe's replacement Henry Clinton intended to take the war against the Americans into the Southern Colonies.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Despite some initial success, British General Cornwallis was besieged by a Franco-American army in Yorktown, Virginia, in September and October 1781.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The French navy cut off Cornwallis's escape and he was forced to surrender in October.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The British wars with France and Spain continued for another two years, but fighting largely ceased in North America.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] In the Treaty of Paris, signed on September 3, 1783, Great Britain acknowledged the sovereignty and independence of the United States, bringing the American Revolutionary War to an end.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The Treaties of Versailles resolved Great Britain's conflicts with France and Spain, and forced Great Britain to cede Tobago, Senegal, and small territories in India to France, and Menorca, West Florida, and East Florida to Spain.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The French and Indian War, part of the wider global conflict known as the Seven Years' War, ended with the 1763 Peace of Paris, which expelled France from their possessions in New France.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The Royal Proclamation of 1763 was designed to refocus colonial expansion north into Nova Scotia and south into Florida, with the Mississippi River as the dividing line between British and Spanish possessions in America.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Settlement was tightly restricted beyond the 1763 limits, and claims west of this line, including by Virginia and Massachusetts, were rescinded.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] With the exception of Virginia and others deprived of rights to western lands, the colonial legislatures agreed on the boundaries but disagreed on where to set them.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Many settlers resented the restrictions entirely, and enforcement required permanent garrisons along the frontier, which led to increasingly bitter disputes over who should pay for them.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The huge debt incurred by the Seven Years' War and demands from British taxpayers for cuts in government expenditure meant Parliament expected the colonies to fund their own defense.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The 1763 to 1765 Grenville ministry instructed the Royal Navy to cease trading smuggled goods and enforce customs duties levied in American ports.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The most important was the 1733 Molasses Act; routinely ignored before 1763, it had a significant economic impact since 85% of New England rum exports were manufactured from imported molasses.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] These measures were followed by the Sugar Act and Stamp Act, which imposed additional taxes on the colonies to pay for defending the western frontier.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The taxes proved highly burdensome, particularly for the poorer classes, and quickly became a source of discontent.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] In July 1765, the Whigs formed the First Rockingham ministry, which repealed the Stamp Act and reduced tax on foreign molasses to help the New England economy, but re-asserted Parliamentary authority in the Declaratory Act.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] However, this did little to end the discontent; in 1768, a riot started in Boston when the authorities seized the sloop *Liberty* on suspicion of smuggling.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Tensions escalated in March 1770 when British troops fired on rock-throwing civilians, killing five in what became known as the Boston Massacre.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The Massacre coincided with the partial repeal of the Townshend Acts by the Tory-based North Ministry.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] North insisted on retaining duty on tea to enshrine Parliament's right to tax the colonies; the amount was minor, but ignored the fact it was that very principle Americans found objectionable.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] In April 1772, colonialists staged the first American tax revolt against British royal authority in Weare, New Hampshire, later referred to as the Pine Tree Riot.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] This would inspire the design of the Pine Tree Flag.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Tensions escalated following the destruction of a customs vessel in the June 1772 Gaspee Affair, then came to a head in 1773.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] A banking crisis led to the near-collapse of the East India Company, which dominated the British economy; to support it, Parliament passed the Tea Act, giving it a trading monopoly in the Thirteen Colonies.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Since most American tea was smuggled by the Dutch, the act was opposed by those who managed the illegal trade, while being seen as another attempt to impose the principle of taxation by Parliament.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] In December 1773, a group called the Sons of Liberty disguised as Mohawks dumped crates of tea into Boston Harbor, an event later known as the Boston Tea Party.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The British Parliament responded by passing the so-called Intolerable Acts, aimed specifically at Massachusetts, although many colonists and members of the Whig opposition considered them a threat to liberty in general.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] This increased sympathy for the Patriot cause locally, in the British Parliament, and in the London press.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Throughout the 18th century, the elected lower houses in the colonial legislatures gradually wrested power from their governors.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Dominated by smaller landowners and merchants, these assemblies now established ad-hoc provincial legislatures, effectively replacing royal control.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] With the exception of Georgia, twelve colonies sent representatives to the First Continental Congress to agree on a unified response to the crisis.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Many of the delegates feared that a boycott would result in war and sent a Petition to the King calling for the repeal of the Intolerable Acts.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] After some debate, on September 17, 1774, Congress endorsed the Massachusetts Suffolk Resolves and on October 20 passed the Continental Association, which instituted economic sanctions and a boycott of goods against Britain.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] While denying its authority over internal American affairs, a faction led by James Duane and future Loyalist Joseph Galloway insisted Congress recognize Parliament's right to regulate colonial trade.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Expecting concessions by the North administration, Congress authorized the colonial legislatures to enforce the boycott; this succeeded in reducing British imports by 97% from 1774 to 1775.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] However, on February 9 Parliament declared Massachusetts to be in rebellion and instituted a blockade of the colony.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] In July, the Restraining Acts limited colonial trade with the British West Indies and Britain and barred New England ships from the Newfoundland cod fisheries.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The tension led to a scramble for control of militia stores, which each assembly was legally obliged to maintain for defense.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] On April 19, a British attempt to secure the Concord arsenal culminated in the Battles of Lexington and Concord, which began the Revolutionary War.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] After the Patriot victory at Concord, moderates in Congress led by John Dickinson drafted the Olive Branch Petition, offering to accept royal authority in return for George III mediating in the dispute.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] However, since the petition was immediately followed by the Declaration of the Causes and Necessity of Taking Up Arms, Colonial Secretary Lord Dartmouth viewed the offer as insincere and refused to present the petition to the king.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Although constitutionally correct, since the monarch could not oppose his own government, it disappointed those Americans who hoped he would mediate in the dispute, while the hostility of his language annoyed even Loyalist members of Congress.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Combined with the Proclamation of Rebellion, issued on August 23 in response to the Battle at Bunker Hill, it ended hopes of a peaceful settlement.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Backed by the Whigs, Parliament initially rejected the imposition of coercive measures by 170 votes, fearing an aggressive policy would drive the Americans towards independence.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] However, by the end of 1774 the collapse of British authority meant both Lord North and George III were convinced war was inevitable.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] After Boston, Gage halted operations and awaited reinforcements; the Irish Parliament approved the recruitment of new regiments, while allowing Catholics to enlist for the first time.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Britain also signed a series of treaties with German states to supply additional troops.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Within a year, it had an army of over 32,000 men in America, the largest ever sent outside Europe at the time.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The employment of German soldiers against people viewed as British citizens was opposed by many in Parliament and by the colonial assemblies; combined with the lack of activity by Gage, opposition to the use of foreign troops allowed the Patriots to take control of the legislatures.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Support for independence was boosted by Thomas Paine's pamphlet *Common Sense*, which was published on January 10, 1776, and argued for American self-government and was widely reprinted.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] To draft the Declaration of Independence, the Second Continental Congress appointed the Committee of Five: Thomas Jefferson, John Adams, Benjamin Franklin, Roger Sherman, and Robert Livingston.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The declaration was written almost exclusively by Jefferson.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Identifying inhabitants of the Thirteen Colonies as "one people", the declaration simultaneously dissolved political links with Britain, while including a long list of alleged violations of "English rights" committed by George III.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] This is also one of the first times that the colonies were referred to as "United States", rather than the more common United Colonies.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] On July 2, Congress voted for independence and published the declaration on July 4.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] At this point, the revolution ceased to be an internal dispute over trade and tax policies between the Thirteen Colonies and Great Britain, becoming a civil war, with each state represented in Congress engaged in a struggle with Britain.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The conflict was also a civil war between American Patriots and American Loyalists.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Patriots generally supported independence from Britain and a new national union in Congress, while Loyalists remained aligned with British rule.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Estimates of numbers vary, one suggestion being the population as a whole was split evenly between committed Patriots, committed Loyalists, and those who were indifferent.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Others calculate the split as 40% Patriot, 40% neutral, 20% Loyalist, but with considerable regional variations.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] At the onset of the war, the Second Continental Congress realized defeating Britain required foreign alliances and intelligence-gathering.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The Committee of Secret Correspondence was formed for "the sole purpose of corresponding with our friends in Great Britain and other parts of the world".
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] From 1775 to 1776, the committee shared information and built alliances through secret correspondence, as well as employing secret agents in Europe to gather intelligence, conduct undercover operations, analyze foreign publications, and initiate Patriot propaganda campaigns.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Paine served as secretary, while Benjamin Franklin and Silas Deane, sent to France, Britain's longtime rival, to recruit military engineers, were instrumental in securing French aid in Paris.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On April 14, 1775, Sir Thomas Gage, Commander-in-Chief, North America and Governor of Massachusetts, received orders to take action against the Patriots.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] He decided to destroy militia ordnance stored at Concord, Massachusetts, and capture John Hancock and Samuel Adams, who were considered the principal instigators of the rebellion.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The operation was to begin around midnight on April 19, in the hope of completing it before the American Patriots could respond.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] However, Paul Revere learned of the plan and notified Captain Parker, commander of the Concord militia, who prepared to resist.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The first action of the war, commonly referred to as the shot heard round the world, was a brief skirmish at Lexington, followed by the full-scale Battles of Lexington and Concord.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] British troops suffered around 300 casualties before withdrawing to Boston, which was then besieged by the militia.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In May 1775, 4,500 British reinforcements arrived under Generals William Howe, John Burgoyne, and Sir Henry Clinton.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On June 17, they seized the Charlestown Peninsula at the Battle of Bunker Hill, a frontal assault in which they suffered over 1,000 casualties.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Dismayed at the costly attack which had gained them little, Gage appealed to London for a larger army, but instead was replaced as commander by Howe.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On June 14, 1775, Congress took control of Patriot forces outside Boston, and Congressional leader John Adams nominated Washington as commander-in-chief of the newly formed Continental Army.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On June 16, Hancock officially proclaimed him "General and Commander in Chief of the army of the United Colonies." He assumed command on July 3, preferring to fortify Dorchester Heights outside Boston rather than assaulting it.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In early March 1776, Colonel Henry Knox arrived with heavy artillery acquired in the Capture of Fort Ticonderoga.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Under cover of darkness, on March 5, Washington placed these on Dorchester Heights, from where they could fire on the town and British ships in Boston Harbor.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Fearing another Bunker Hill, Howe evacuated the city on March 17 without further loss and sailed to Halifax, Nova Scotia, while Washington moved south to New York City.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Beginning in August 1775, American privateers raided towns in Nova Scotia, including Saint John, Charlottetown, and Yarmouth.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In 1776, John Paul Jones and Jonathan Eddy attacked Canso and Fort Cumberland respectively.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] British officials in Quebec began negotiating with the Iroquois for their support, while US envoys urged them to remain neutral.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Aware of Native American leanings toward the British and fearing an Anglo-Indian attack from Canada, Congress authorized a second invasion in April 1775.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] After the defeat at the Battle of Quebec on December 31, the Americans maintained a loose blockade of the city until they retreated on May 6, 1776.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] A second defeat at Trois-Rivières on June 8 ended operations in Quebec.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] British pursuit was initially blocked by American naval vessels on Lake Champlain until victory at Valcour Island on October 11 forced the Americans to withdraw to Fort Ticonderoga, while in December an uprising in Nova Scotia sponsored by Massachusetts was defeated at Fort Cumberland.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] These failures impacted public support for the Patriot cause, and aggressive anti-Loyalist policies in the New England colonies alienated the Canadians.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In Virginia, Dunmore's Proclamation on November 7, 1775, promised freedom to any slaves who fled their Patriot masters and agreed to fight for the Crown.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] British forces were defeated at Great Bridge on December 9 and took refuge on British ships anchored near Norfolk.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] When the Third Virginia Convention refused to disband its militia or accept martial law, Lord Dunmore ordered the Burning of Norfolk on January 1, 1776.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The siege of Savage's Old Fields began on November 19 in South Carolina between Loyalist and Patriot militias, and the Loyalists were subsequently driven out of the colony in the Snow Campaign.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Loyalists were recruited in North Carolina to reassert British rule in the South, but they were decisively defeated in the Battle of Moore's Creek Bridge.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] A British expedition sent to reconquer South Carolina launched an attack on Charleston in the Battle of Sullivan's Island on June 28, 1776, but it failed.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] A shortage of gunpowder led Congress to authorize a naval expedition against the Bahamas to secure ordnance stored there.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On March 3, 1776, an American squadron under the command of Esek Hopkins landed at the east end of Nassau and encountered minimal resistance at Fort Montagu.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Hopkins' troops then marched on Fort Nassau.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Hopkins had promised governor Montfort Browne and the civilian inhabitants that their lives and property would not be in any danger if they offered no resistance; they complied.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Hopkins captured large stores of powder and other munitions that was so great he had to impress an extra ship in the harbor to transport the supplies back home, when he departed on March 17.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] A month later, after a brief skirmish with HMS *Glasgow*, they returned to New London, Connecticut, the base for American naval operations.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] After regrouping at Halifax in Nova Scotia, Howe set sail for New York in June 1776 and began landing troops on Staten Island near the entrance to New York Harbor on July 2.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The Americans rejected Howe's informal attempt to negotiate peace on July 30; Washington knew that an attack on the city was imminent and realized that he needed advance information to deal with disciplined British regular troops.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On August 12, 1776, Patriot Thomas Knowlton was ordered to form an elite group for reconnaissance and secret missions.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Knowlton's Rangers, which included Nathan Hale, became the Army's first intelligence unit.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] When Washington was driven off Long Island, he soon realized that he would need to professionalize military intelligence.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] With aid from Benjamin Tallmadge, Washington launched the six-man Culper spy ring.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The efforts of Washington and the Culper Spy Ring substantially increased the effective allocation and deployment of Continental regiments in the field.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Throughout the war, Washington spent more than 10 percent of his total military funds on military intelligence.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Washington split the Continental Army into positions on Manhattan and across the East River in western Long Island.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On August 27 at the Battle of Long Island, Howe outflanked Washington and forced him back to Brooklyn Heights, but he did not attempt to encircle Washington's forces.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Through the night of August 28, Knox bombarded the British.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Knowing they were up against overwhelming odds, Washington ordered the assembly of a war council on August 29; all agreed to retreat to Manhattan.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Washington quickly had his troops assembled and ferried them across the East River to Manhattan on flat-bottomed freight boats without any losses in men or ordnance, leaving General Thomas Mifflin's regiments as a rearguard.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Howe met with a delegation from the Second Continental Congress at the September Staten Island Peace Conference, but it failed to conclude peace, largely because the British delegates only had the authority to offer pardons and could not recognize independence.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On September 15, Howe seized control of New York City when the British landed at Kip's Bay and unsuccessfully engaged the Americans at the Battle of Harlem Heights the following day.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On October 18, Howe failed to encircle the Americans at the Battle of Pell's Point, and the Americans withdrew.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Howe declined to close with Washington's army on October 28 at the Battle of White Plains and instead attacked a hill that was of no strategic value.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Washington's retreat isolated his remaining forces and the British captured Fort Washington on November 16.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The British victory there amounted to Washington's most disastrous defeat with the loss of 3,000 prisoners.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The remaining American regiments on Long Island fell back four days later.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] General Henry Clinton wanted to pursue Washington's disorganized army, but he was first required to commit 6,000 troops to capture Newport, Rhode Island, to secure the Loyalist port.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] General Charles Cornwallis pursued Washington, but Howe ordered him to halt.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The outlook following the defeat at Fort Washington appeared bleak for the American cause.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The reduced Continental Army had dwindled to fewer than 5,000 men and was reduced further when enlistments expired at the end of the year.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Popular support wavered, and morale declined.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On December 20, 1776, the Continental Congress abandoned the revolutionary capital of Philadelphia and moved to Baltimore, where it remained until February 27, 1777.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Loyalist activity surged in the wake of the American defeat, especially in New York state.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In London, news of the victorious Long Island campaign was well received with festivities held in the capital.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Strategic deficiencies among Patriot forces were evident: Washington divided a numerically weaker army in the face of a stronger one, his inexperienced staff misread the military situation, and American troops fled in the face of enemy fire.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The successes led to predictions that the British could win within a year.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The British established winter quarters in the New York City area and anticipated renewed campaigning the following spring.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On the night of December 25–26, 1776, Washington crossed the Delaware River, leading a column of Continental Army troops from today's Bucks County, Pennsylvania, to today's Mercer County, New Jersey, in a logistically challenging and dangerous operation.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Meanwhile, the Hessians were involved in numerous clashes with small bands of Patriots and were often aroused by false alarms at night in the weeks before the actual Battle of Trenton.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] By Christmas they were tired, while a heavy snowstorm led their commander, Colonel Johann Rall, to assume no significant attack would occur.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] At daybreak on the 26th, the American Patriots surprised and overwhelmed Rall and his troops, who lost over 20 killed including Rall, while 900 prisoners, German cannons and supplies were captured.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The Battle of Trenton restored the American army's morale, reinvigorated the Patriot cause, and dispelled their fear of what they regarded as Hessian "mercenaries".
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] A British attempt to retake Trenton was repulsed at Assunpink Creek on January 2; during the night, Washington outmaneuvered Cornwallis, then defeated his rearguard in the Battle of Princeton the following day.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The two victories helped convince the French that the Americans were worthy military allies.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] After his success at Princeton, Washington entered winter quarters at Morristown, New Jersey, where he remained until May and received Congressional direction to inoculate all Patriot troops against smallpox.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] With the exception of a minor skirmishing between the two armies which continued until March, Howe made no attempt to attack the Americans.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The 1776 campaign demonstrated that regaining New England would be a prolonged affair, which led to a change in British strategy to isolating the north by taking control of the Hudson River, allowing them to focus on the south where Loyalist support was believed to be substantial.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In December 1776, Howe wrote to the Colonial Secretary Lord Germain, proposing a limited offensive against Philadelphia, while a second force moved down the Hudson from Canada.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Burgoyne supplied several alternatives, all of which gave him responsibility for the offensive, with Howe remaining on the defensive.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The option selected required him to lead the main force south from Montreal down the Hudson Valley, while a detachment under Barry St.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The two would meet at Albany, leaving Howe to decide whether to join them.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Reasonable in principle, this did not account for the logistical difficulties involved and Burgoyne erroneously assumed Howe would remain on the defensive; Germain's failure to make this clear meant he opted to attack Philadelphia instead.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] With a mixed force of British regulars, professional German soldiers and Canadian militia Burgoyne set out on June 14, 1777, and captured Fort Ticonderoga on July 5.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] As General Horatio Gates retreated, his troops blocked roads, destroyed bridges, dammed streams, and stripped the area of food.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] This slowed Burgoyne's progress and forced him to send out large foraging expeditions; one of more than 700 British troops were captured at the Battle of Bennington on August 16.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] St Leger moved east and besieged Fort Stanwix; despite defeating an American relief force at the Battle of Oriskany on August 6, St.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Leger was abandoned by his Indian allies and withdrew to Quebec on August 22.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Now isolated and outnumbered by Gates, Burgoyne continued onto Albany rather than retreating to Fort Ticonderoga, reaching Saratoga on September 13.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] He asked Clinton for support while constructing defenses around the town.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Morale among his troops rapidly declined, and an unsuccessful attempt to break past Gates at the Battle of Freeman Farms on September 19 resulted in 600 British casualties.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] When Clinton advised he could not reach them, Burgoyne's subordinates advised retreat; a reconnaissance in force on October 7 was repulsed by Gates at the Battle of Bemis Heights, forcing them back into Saratoga with heavy losses.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] By October 11, all hope of British escape had vanished; persistent rain reduced the camp to a "squalid hell" and supplies were dangerously low.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Burgoyne capitulated on October 17; around 6,222 soldiers, including German forces commanded by General Friedrich Adolf Riedesel, surrendered their arms before being taken to Boston, where they were to be transported to England.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] After securing additional supplies, Howe made another attempt on Philadelphia by landing his troops in Chesapeake Bay on August 24.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] He now compounded failure to support Burgoyne by missing repeated opportunities to destroy his opponent: despite defeating Washington at the Battle of Brandywine on September 11, he then allowed him to withdraw in good order.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] After dispersing an American detachment at Paoli on September 20, Cornwallis occupied Philadelphia on September 26, with the main force of 9,000 under Howe based just to the north at Germantown.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Washington attacked them on October 4, but was repulsed.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] To prevent Howe's forces in Philadelphia being resupplied by sea, the Patriots erected Fort Mifflin and nearby Fort Mercer on the east and west banks of the Delaware respectively, and placed obstacles in the river south of the city.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] This was supported by a small flotilla of Continental Navy ships on the Delaware, supplemented by the Pennsylvania State Navy, commanded by John Hazelwood.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] An attempt by the Royal Navy to take the forts in the October 20 to 22 Battle of Red Bank failed; a second attack captured Fort Mifflin on November 16, while Fort Mercer was abandoned two days later when Cornwallis breached the walls.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] His supply lines secured, Howe tried to tempt Washington into giving battle, but after inconclusive skirmishing at the Battle of White Marsh from December 5 to 8, he withdrew to Philadelphia for the winter.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On December 19, the Americans followed suit and entered winter quarters at Valley Forge.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] As Washington's domestic opponents contrasted his lack of battlefield success with Gates' victory at Saratoga, foreign observers such as Frederick the Great were equally impressed with Washington's command at Germantown, which demonstrated resilience and determination.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Over the winter, poor conditions, supply problems and low morale resulted in 2,000 deaths, with another 3,000 unfit for duty due to lack of shoes.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] However, Baron Friedrich Wilhelm von Steuben took the opportunity to introduce Prussian Army drill and infantry tactics to "model companies" in each Continental Army regiment, who then instructed their home units.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Despite Valley Forge being only twenty miles away, Howe made no effort to attack their camp, an action some critics argue could have ended the war.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Like his predecessors, French foreign minister Vergennes considered the 1763 Peace a national humiliation and viewed the war as an opportunity to weaken Britain.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] He initially avoided open conflict, but allowed American ships to take on cargoes in French ports, a technical violation of neutrality.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Vergennes persuaded Louis XVI to secretly fund a government front company to purchase munitions for the Patriots, carried in neutral Dutch ships and imported through Sint Eustatius in the Caribbean.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Many Americans opposed a French alliance, fearing to "exchange one tyranny for another", but this changed after a series of military setbacks in early 1776.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] As France had nothing to gain from the colonies reconciling with Britain, Congress had three choices: making peace on British terms, continuing the struggle on their own, or proclaiming independence, guaranteed by France.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Although the Declaration of Independence had wide public support, over 20% of Congressmen voted against an alliance with France.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Congress agreed to the treaty with reluctance and as the war moved in their favor increasingly lost interest in it.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Silas Deane was sent to Paris to begin negotiations with Vergennes, whose key objectives were replacing Britain as the United States' primary commercial and military partner while securing the French West Indies from American expansion.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] These islands were extremely valuable; in 1772, the value of sugar and coffee produced by Saint-Domingue on its own exceeded that of all American exports combined.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Talks progressed slowly until October 1777, when British defeat at Saratoga and their apparent willingness to negotiate peace convinced Vergennes only a permanent alliance could prevent the "disaster" of Anglo-American rapprochement.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Assurances of formal French support allowed Congress to reject the Carlisle Peace Commission and insist on nothing short of complete independence.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On February 6, 1778, France and the United States signed the Treaty of Amity and Commerce regulating trade between the two countries, followed by a defensive military alliance against Britain, the Treaty of Alliance.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In return for French guarantees of American independence, Congress undertook to defend their interests in the West Indies, while both sides agreed not to make a separate peace; conflict over these provisions would lead to the 1798 to 1800 Quasi-War.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Charles III of Spain was invited to join on the same terms but refused, largely due to concerns over the impact of the Revolution on Spanish colonies in the Americas.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Spain had complained on multiple occasions about encroachment by American settlers into Louisiana, a problem that could only get worse once the United States replaced Britain.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Although Spain ultimately made important contributions to American success, in the Treaty of Aranjuez, Charles agreed only to support France's war with Britain outside America, in return for help in recovering Gibraltar, Menorca and Spanish Florida.
[src:american-revolutionary-war/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The terms were confidential since several conflicted with American aims; for example, the French claimed exclusive control of the Newfoundland cod fisheries, a non-negotiable for colonies like Massachusetts.
